# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermodynamics-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Entropy is central to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that the entropy of an isolated system left to spontaneous evolution cannot decrease with time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] As a result, isolated systems evolve toward thermodynamic equilibrium, where the entropy is highest.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] "High" entropy means that energy is more disordered or dispersed, while "low" entropy means that energy is more ordered or concentrated.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] A consequence of the second law of thermodynamics is that certain processes are irreversible.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The thermodynamic concept was referred to by Scottish scientist and engineer William Rankine in 1850 with the names *thermodynamic function* and *heat-potential*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In 1865, German physicist Rudolf Clausius, one of the leading founders of the field of thermodynamics, defined it as the quotient of an infinitesimal amount of heat to the instantaneous temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] He initially described it as *transformation-content*, in German *Verwandlungsinhalt*, and later coined the term *entropy* from a Greek word for *transformation*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Austrian physicist Ludwig Boltzmann explained entropy as the measure of the number of possible microscopic arrangements or states of individual atoms and molecules of a system that comply with the macroscopic condition of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] He used an analogy with how water falls in a water wheel.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] That was an early insight into the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Carnot reasoned that if the body of the working substance, such as a body of steam, is returned to its original state at the end of a complete engine cycle, "no change occurs in the condition of the working body".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The first law of thermodynamics, deduced from the heat–friction experiments of James Joule in 1843, expresses the concept of energy and its conservation in all processes; the first law, however, is unsuitable for separately quantifying the effects of friction and dissipation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In the 1850s and 1860s, German physicist Rudolf Clausius objected to the supposition that no change occurs in the working body, and gave that change a mathematical interpretation, by questioning the nature of the inherent loss of usable heat when work is done, e.g., heat produced by friction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] He described his observations as a dissipative use of energy, resulting in a *transformation-content* (*Verwandlungsinhalt* in German), of a thermodynamic system or working body of chemical species during a change of state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] That was in contrast to earlier views, based on the theories of Isaac Newton, that heat was an indestructible particle that had mass.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Clausius discovered that the non-usable energy increases as steam proceeds from inlet to exhaust in a steam engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The word was adopted into the English language in 1868.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Later, scientists such as Ludwig Boltzmann, Josiah Willard Gibbs, and James Clerk Maxwell gave entropy a statistical basis.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In 1877, Boltzmann visualized a probabilistic way to measure the entropy of an ensemble of ideal gas particles, in which he defined entropy as proportional to the natural logarithm of the number of microstates such a gas could occupy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The proportionality constant in this definition, called the Boltzmann constant, has become one of the defining universal constants for the modern International System of Units (SI).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Henceforth, the essential problem in statistical thermodynamics has been to determine the distribution of a given amount of energy *E* over *N* identical systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Constantin Carathéodory, a Greek mathematician, linked entropy with a mathematical definition of irreversibility, in terms of trajectories and integrability.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In 1865, Clausius named the concept of "the differential of a quantity which depends on the configuration of the system" *entropy* (*Entropie*) after the Greek word for 'transformation'.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This term was formed by replacing the root of ἔργον ('ergon', 'work') by that of τροπή ('tropy', 'transformation').
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Leon Cooper added that in this way "he succeeded in coining a word that meant the same thing to everybody: nothing".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The concept of entropy is described by two principal approaches, the macroscopic perspective of classical thermodynamics, and the microscopic description central to statistical mechanics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The classical approach defines entropy in terms of macroscopically measurable physical properties, such as bulk mass, volume, pressure, and temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The statistical definition of entropy defines it in terms of the statistics of the motions of the microscopic constituents of a system — modelled at first classically, e.g.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Newtonian particles constituting a gas, and later quantum-mechanically (photons, phonons, spins, etc.).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The two approaches form a consistent, unified view of the same phenomenon as expressed in the second law of thermodynamics, which has found universal applicability to physical processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Many thermodynamic properties are defined by physical variables that define a state of thermodynamic equilibrium, which essentially are state variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] State variables depend only on the equilibrium condition, not on the path evolution to that state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] State variables can be functions of state, also called state functions, in a sense that one state variable is a mathematical function of other state variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Often, if some properties of a system are determined, they are sufficient to determine the state of the system and thus other properties' values.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For example, temperature and pressure of a given quantity of gas determine its state, and thus also its volume via the ideal gas law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] A system composed of a pure substance of a single phase at a particular uniform temperature and pressure is determined, and is thus a particular state, and has a particular volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The fact that entropy is a function of state makes it useful.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In the Carnot cycle, the working fluid returns to the same state that it had at the start of the cycle, hence the change or line integral of any state function, such as entropy, over this reversible cycle is zero.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In contrast, an irreversible process increases the total entropy of the system and surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Any process that happens quickly enough to deviate from the thermal equilibrium cannot be reversible; the total entropy increases, and the potential for maximum work to be done during the process is lost.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The concept of entropy arose from Rudolf Clausius's study of the Carnot cycle which is a thermodynamic cycle performed by a Carnot heat engine as a reversible heat engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] According to Carnot's theorem, a heat engine with two thermal reservoirs can produce a work ${\textstyle W}$ if and only if there is a temperature difference between reservoirs.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Originally, Carnot did not distinguish between heats ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {H}}}$ and ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {C}}}$ , as he assumed caloric theory to be valid and hence that the total heat in the system was conserved.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] But in fact, the magnitude of heat ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {H}}}$ is greater than the magnitude of heat ${\textstyle Q_{\mathsf {C}}}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The possibility that the Carnot function could be the temperature as measured from a zero point of temperature was suggested by Joule in a letter to Kelvin.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This allowed Kelvin to establish his absolute temperature scale.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] It is known that a work ${\textstyle W>0}$ produced by an engine over a cycle equals to a net heat ${\textstyle Q_{\Sigma }=\left\vert Q_{\mathsf {H}}\right\vert -\left\vert Q_{\mathsf {C}}\right\vert }$ absorbed over a cycle.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Which means there exists a state function ${\textstyle U}$ with a change of ${\textstyle \mathrm {d} U=\delta Q-\mathrm {d} W}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] It is called an internal energy and forms a central concept for the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Clausius called this state function *entropy*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Notably, any machine or cyclic process converting heat into work (i.e., heat engine) that is claimed to produce an efficiency greater than the one of Carnot is not viable — due to violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For further analysis of sufficiently discrete systems, such as an assembly of particles, statistical thermodynamics must be used.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Additionally, descriptions of devices operating near the limit of de Broglie waves, e.g. photovoltaic cells, have to be consistent with quantum statistics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The thermodynamic definition of entropy was developed in the early 1850s by Rudolf Clausius and essentially describes how to measure the entropy of an isolated system in thermodynamic equilibrium with its parts.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Clausius created the term entropy as an extensive thermodynamic variable that was shown to be useful in characterizing the Carnot cycle.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Heat transfer in the isotherm steps (isothermal expansion and isothermal compression) of the Carnot cycle was found to be proportional to the temperature of a system (known as its absolute temperature).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This relationship was expressed in an increment of entropy that is equal to incremental heat transfer divided by temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Entropy was found to vary in the thermodynamic cycle but eventually returned to the same value at the end of every cycle.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thus it was found to be a function of state, specifically a thermodynamic state of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] While Clausius based his definition on a reversible process, there are also irreversible processes that change entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Following the second law of thermodynamics, entropy of an isolated system always increases for irreversible processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The difference between an isolated system and closed system is that energy may *not* flow to and from an isolated system, but energy flow to and from a closed system is possible.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Nevertheless, for both closed and isolated systems, and indeed, also in open systems, irreversible thermodynamics processes may occur.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] According to the Clausius equality, for a reversible cyclic thermodynamic process: $\oint {\frac {\delta Q_{\mathsf {rev}}}{T}}=0$ which means the line integral ${\textstyle \int _{L}{\delta Q_{\mathsf {rev}}/T}}$ is path-independent.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thus we can define a state function ${\textstyle S}$ , called *entropy*: $\mathrm {d} S={\frac {\delta Q_{\mathsf {rev}}}{T}}$ Therefore, thermodynamic entropy has the dimension of energy divided by temperature, and the unit joule per kelvin (J/K) in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] To find the entropy difference between any two states of the system, the integral must be evaluated for some reversible path between the initial and final states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Since an entropy is a state function, the entropy change of the system for an irreversible path is the same as for a reversible path between the same two states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] However, the heat transferred to or from the surroundings is different as well as its entropy change.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] We can calculate the change of entropy only by integrating the above formula.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] To obtain the absolute value of the entropy, we consider the third law of thermodynamics: perfect crystals at the absolute zero have an entropy ${\textstyle S=0}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] From a macroscopic perspective, in classical thermodynamics the entropy is interpreted as a state function of a thermodynamic system: that is, a property depending only on the current state of the system, independent of how that state came to be achieved.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In any process, where the system gives up $\Delta E$ of energy to the surrounding at the temperature ${\textstyle T}$ , its entropy falls by ${\textstyle \Delta S}$ and at least ${\textstyle T\cdot \Delta S}$ of that energy must be given up to the system's surroundings as a heat.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Otherwise, this process cannot go forward.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In classical thermodynamics, the entropy of a system is defined if and only if it is in a thermodynamic equilibrium (though a chemical equilibrium is not required: for example, the entropy of a mixture of two moles of hydrogen and one mole of oxygen in standard conditions is well-defined).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The statistical definition was developed by Ludwig Boltzmann in the 1870s by analysing the statistical behaviour of the microscopic components of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Boltzmann showed that this definition of entropy was equivalent to the thermodynamic entropy to within a constant factor—known as the Boltzmann constant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In short, the thermodynamic definition of entropy provides the experimental verification of entropy, while the statistical definition of entropy extends the concept, providing an explanation and a deeper understanding of its nature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The interpretation of entropy in statistical mechanics is the measure of uncertainty, disorder, or *mixedupness* in the phrase of Gibbs, which remains about a system after its observable macroscopic properties, such as temperature, pressure and volume, have been taken into account.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For a given set of macroscopic variables, the entropy measures the degree to which the probability of the system is spread out over different possible microstates.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In contrast to the macrostate, which characterizes plainly observable average quantities, a microstate specifies all molecular details about the system including the position and momentum of every molecule.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The more such states are available to the system with appreciable probability, the greater the entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In statistical mechanics, entropy is a measure of the number of ways a system can be arranged, often taken to be a measure of "disorder" (the higher the entropy, the higher the disorder).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This definition describes the entropy as being proportional to the natural logarithm of the number of possible microscopic configurations of the individual atoms and molecules of the system (microstates) that could cause the observed macroscopic state (macrostate) of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The constant of proportionality is the Boltzmann constant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The Boltzmann constant, and therefore entropy, have dimensions of energy divided by temperature, which has a unit of joules per kelvin (J⋅K−1) in the International System of Units (or kg⋅m2⋅s−2⋅K−1 in terms of base units).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The entropy of a substance is usually given as an intensive property — either entropy per unit mass (SI unit: J⋅K−1⋅kg−1) or entropy per unit amount of substance (SI unit: J⋅K−1⋅mol−1).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In a general case the expression is: $S=-k_{\mathsf {B}}\ \mathrm {tr} {\left({\hat {\rho }}\times \ln {\hat {\rho }}\right)}$ where ${\textstyle {\hat {\rho }}}$ is a density matrix, $\mathrm {tr}$ is a trace operator and $\ln$ is a matrix logarithm.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The density matrix formalism is not required if the system is in thermal equilibrium so long as the basis states are chosen to be eigenstates of the Hamiltonian.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For most practical purposes it can be taken as the fundamental definition of entropy since all other formulae for ${\textstyle S}$ can be derived from it, but not vice versa.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Usually, this assumption is justified for an isolated system in a thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Then in case of an isolated system the previous formula reduces to: $S=k_{\mathsf {B}}\ln {\Omega }$ In thermodynamics, such a system is one with a fixed volume, number of molecules, and internal energy, called a microcanonical ensemble.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The most general interpretation of entropy is as a measure of the extent of uncertainty about a system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The equilibrium state of a system maximizes the entropy because it does not reflect all information about the initial conditions, except for the conserved variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This uncertainty is not of the everyday subjective kind, but rather the uncertainty inherent to the experimental method and interpretative model.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The interpretative model has a central role in determining entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The qualifier "for a given set of macroscopic variables" above has deep implications when two observers use different sets of macroscopic variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For example, consider observer A using variables ${\textstyle U}$ , ${\textstyle V}$ , ${\textstyle W}$ and observer B using variables ${\textstyle U}$ , ${\textstyle V}$ , ${\textstyle W}$ , ${\textstyle X}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] If observer B changes variable ${\textstyle X}$ , then observer A will see a violation of the second law of thermodynamics, since he does not possess information about variable ${\textstyle X}$ and its influence on the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In other words, one must choose a complete set of macroscopic variables to describe the system, i.e. every independent parameter that may change during experiment.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Entropy can also be defined for any Markov processes with reversible dynamics and the detailed balance property.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In Boltzmann's 1896 *Lectures on Gas Theory*, he showed that this expression gives a measure of entropy for systems of atoms and molecules in the gas phase, thus providing a measure for the entropy of classical thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In a thermodynamic system, pressure and temperature tend to become uniform over time because the equilibrium state has higher probability (more possible combinations of microstates) than any other state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Over time the temperature of the glass and its contents and the temperature of the room become equal.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In other words, the entropy of the room has decreased as some of its energy has been dispersed to the ice and water, of which the entropy has increased.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] However, as calculated in the example, the entropy of the system of ice and water has increased more than the entropy of the surrounding room has decreased.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In an isolated system such as the room and ice water taken together, the dispersal of energy from warmer to cooler always results in a net increase in entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thus, when the "universe" of the room and ice water system has reached a temperature equilibrium, the entropy change from the initial state is at a maximum.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The entropy of the thermodynamic system is a measure of how far the equalisation has progressed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic entropy is a non-conserved state function that is of great importance in the sciences of physics and chemistry.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Historically, the concept of entropy evolved to explain why some processes (permitted by conservation laws) occur spontaneously while their time reversals (also permitted by conservation laws) do not; systems tend to progress in the direction of increasing entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For isolated systems, entropy never decreases.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This fact has several important consequences in science: first, it prohibits "perpetual motion" machines; and second, it implies the arrow of entropy has the same direction as the arrow of time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Increases in the total entropy of system and surroundings correspond to irreversible changes, because some energy is expended as waste heat, limiting the amount of work a system can do.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Unlike many other functions of state, entropy cannot be directly observed but must be calculated.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Absolute standard molar entropy of a substance can be calculated from the measured temperature dependence of its heat capacity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The molar entropy of ions is obtained as a difference in entropy from a reference state defined as zero entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The second law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of an isolated system must increase or remain constant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Therefore, entropy is not a conserved quantity: for example, in an isolated system with non-uniform temperature, heat might irreversibly flow and the temperature become more uniform such that entropy increases.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Chemical reactions cause changes in entropy and system entropy, in conjunction with enthalpy, plays an important role in determining in which direction a chemical reaction spontaneously proceeds.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Rice University's definition of entropy is that it is "a measurement of a system's disorder and its inability to do work in a system".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For instance, a substance at uniform temperature is at maximum entropy and cannot drive a heat engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] A substance at non-uniform temperature is at a lower entropy (than if the heat distribution is allowed to even out) and some of the thermal energy can drive a heat engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] A special case of entropy increase, the entropy of mixing, occurs when two or more different substances are mixed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] If the substances are at the same temperature and pressure, there is no net exchange of heat or work – the entropy change is entirely due to the mixing of the different substances.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] At a statistical mechanical level, this results due to the change in available volume per particle with mixing.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] These proofs are based on the probability density of microstates of the generalised Boltzmann distribution and the identification of the thermodynamic internal energy as the ensemble average ${\textstyle U=\left\langle E_{i}\right\rangle }$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic relations are then employed to derive the well-known Gibbs entropy formula.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] However, the equivalence between the Gibbs entropy formula and the thermodynamic definition of entropy is not a fundamental thermodynamic relation but rather a consequence of the form of the generalized Boltzmann distribution.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic state functions are described by ensemble averages of random variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] At infinite temperature, all the microstates have the same probability.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that, in general, the total entropy of any system does not decrease other than by increasing the entropy of some other system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Hence, in a system isolated from its environment, the entropy of that system tends not to decrease.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] It follows that heat cannot flow from a colder body to a hotter body without the application of work to the colder body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] As a result, there is no possibility of a perpetual motion machine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] It follows that a reduction in the increase of entropy in a specified process, such as a chemical reaction, means that it is energetically more efficient.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] It follows from the second law of thermodynamics that the entropy of a system that is not isolated may decrease.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] An air conditioner, for example, may cool the air in a room, thus reducing the entropy of the air of that system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The heat expelled from the room (the system), which the air conditioner transports and discharges to the outside air, always makes a bigger contribution to the entropy of the environment than the decrease of the entropy of the air of that system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thus, the total of entropy of the room plus the entropy of the environment increases, in agreement with the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In mechanics, the second law in conjunction with the fundamental thermodynamic relation places limits on a system's ability to do useful work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The entropy change of a system at temperature ${\textstyle T}$ absorbing an infinitesimal amount of heat ${\textstyle \delta q}$ in a reversible way, is given by ${\textstyle \delta q/T}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] More explicitly, an energy ${\textstyle T_{R}S}$ is not available to do useful work, where ${\textstyle T_{R}}$ is the temperature of the coldest accessible reservoir or heat sink external to the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Statistical mechanics demonstrates that entropy is governed by probability, thus allowing for a decrease in disorder even in an isolated system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Although this is possible, such an event has a small probability of occurring, making it unlikely.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The applicability of a second law of thermodynamics is limited to systems in or sufficiently near equilibrium state, so that they have defined entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Some inhomogeneous systems out of thermodynamic equilibrium still satisfy the hypothesis of local thermodynamic equilibrium, so that entropy density is locally defined as an intensive quantity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For such systems, there may apply a principle of maximum time rate of entropy production.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] It states that such a system may evolve to a steady state that maximises its time rate of entropy production.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This does not mean that such a system is necessarily always in a condition of maximum time rate of entropy production; it means that it may evolve to such a steady state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The entropy of a system depends on its internal energy and its external parameters, such as its volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In the thermodynamic limit, this fact leads to an equation relating the change in the internal energy ${\textstyle U}$ to changes in the entropy and the external parameters.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This relation is known as the *fundamental thermodynamic relation*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The fundamental thermodynamic relation implies many thermodynamic identities that are valid in general, independent of the microscopic details of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Important examples are the Maxwell relations and the relations between heat capacities.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic entropy is central in chemical thermodynamics, enabling changes to be quantified and the outcome of reactions predicted.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The second law of thermodynamics states that entropy in an isolated system — the combination of a subsystem under study and its surroundings — increases during all spontaneous chemical and physical processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The Clausius equation introduces the measurement of entropy change which describes the direction and quantifies the magnitude of simple changes such as heat transfer between systems — always from hotter body to cooler one spontaneously.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thermodynamic entropy is an extensive property, meaning that it scales with the size or extent of a system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In many processes it is useful to specify the entropy as an intensive property independent of the size, as a specific entropy characteristic of the type of system studied.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Specific entropy may be expressed relative to a unit of mass, typically the kilogram (unit: J⋅kg−1⋅K−1).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Alternatively, in chemistry, it is also referred to one mole of substance, in which case it is called the *molar entropy* with a unit of J⋅mol−1⋅K−1.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Thus, when one mole of substance at about 0 K is warmed by its surroundings to 298 K, the sum of the incremental values of ${\textstyle q_{\mathsf {rev}}/T}$ constitute each element's or compound's standard molar entropy, an indicator of the amount of energy stored by a substance at 298 K.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Entropy change also measures the mixing of substances as a summation of their relative quantities in the final mixture.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Entropy is equally essential in predicting the extent and direction of complex chemical reactions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The spontaneity of a chemical or physical process is governed by the Gibbs free energy change (ΔG), as defined by the equation ΔG = ΔH − TΔS, where ΔH represents the enthalpy change, ΔS the entropy change, and T the temperature in Kelvin.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] A negative ΔG indicates a thermodynamically favorable (spontaneous) process, while a positive ΔG denotes a non-spontaneous one.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] When both ΔH and ΔS are positive (endothermic, entropy-increasing), the reaction becomes spontaneous at sufficiently high temperatures, as the TΔS term dominates.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Conversely, if both ΔH and ΔS are negative (exothermic, entropy-decreasing), spontaneity occurs only at low temperatures, where the enthalpy term prevails.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Reactions with ΔH < 0 and ΔS > 0 (exothermic and entropy-increasing) are spontaneous at all temperatures, while those with ΔH > 0 and ΔS < 0 (endothermic and entropy-decreasing) are non-spontaneous regardless of temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] These principles underscore the interplay between energy exchange, disorder, and temperature in determining the direction of natural processes, from phase transitions to biochemical reactions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] A 2011 study in *Science* estimated the world's technological capacity to store and communicate optimally compressed information normalised on the most effective compression algorithms available in the year 2007, therefore estimating the entropy of the technologically available sources.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The author's estimate that humankind's technological capacity to store information grew from 2.6 (entropically compressed) exabytes in 1986 to 295 (entropically compressed) exabytes in 2007.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The world's technological capacity to receive information through one-way broadcast networks was 432 exabytes of (entropically compressed) information in 1986, to 1.9 zettabytes in 2007.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The world's effective capacity to exchange information through two-way telecommunication networks was 281 petabytes of (entropically compressed) information in 1986, to 65 (entropically compressed) exabytes in 2007.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In chemical engineering, the principles of thermodynamics are commonly applied to "open systems", i.e. those in which heat, work, and mass flow across the system boundary.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In general, flow of heat ${\textstyle {\dot {Q}}}$ , flow of shaft work ${\textstyle {\dot {W}}_{\mathsf {S}}}$ and pressure-volume work ${\textstyle P{\dot {V}}}$ across the system boundaries cause changes in the entropy of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Heat transfer entails entropy transfer ${\textstyle {\dot {Q}}/T}$ , where ${\textstyle T}$ is the absolute thermodynamic temperature of the system at the point of the heat flow.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] If there are mass flows across the system boundaries, they also influence the total entropy of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] This account, in terms of heat and work, is valid only for cases in which the work and heat transfers are by paths physically distinct from the paths of entry and exit of matter from the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] To derive a generalised entropy balanced equation, we start with the general balance equation for the change in any extensive quantity ${\textstyle \theta }$ in a thermodynamic system, a quantity that may be either conserved, such as energy, or non-conserved, such as entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The nomenclature "entropy balance" is misleading and often deemed inappropriate because entropy is not a conserved quantity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] In other words, the term ${\textstyle {\dot {S}}_{\mathsf {gen}}}$ is never a known quantity but always a derived one based on the expression above.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Therefore, the open system version of the second law is more appropriately described as the "entropy generation equation" since it specifies that: ${\dot {S}}_{\mathsf {gen}}\geq 0$ with zero for reversible process and positive values for irreversible one.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] For certain simple transformations in systems of constant composition, the entropy changes are given by simple formulas.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] These equations also apply for expansion into a finite vacuum or a throttling process, where the temperature, internal energy and enthalpy for an ideal gas remain constant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] provided that the constant-pressure molar heat capacity (or specific heat) ${\textstyle C_{\mathrm {P} }}$ is constant and that no phase transition occurs in this temperature interval.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Similarly at constant volume, the entropy change is: $\Delta S=nC_{\mathrm {V} }\ln {\frac {T}{T_{0}}}$ where the constant-volume molar heat capacity ${\textstyle C_{\mathrm {V} }}$ is constant and there is no phase change.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] At low temperatures near absolute zero, heat capacities of solids quickly drop off to near zero, so the assumption of constant heat capacity does not apply.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Since entropy is a state function, the entropy change of any process in which temperature and volume both vary is the same as for a path divided into two steps – heating at constant volume and expansion at constant temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] Reversible phase transitions occur at constant temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p01] The reversible heat is the enthalpy change for the transition, and the entropy change is the enthalpy change divided by the thermodynamic temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] As a fundamental aspect of thermodynamics and physics, several different approaches to entropy beyond that of Clausius and Boltzmann are valid.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] In Boltzmann's analysis in terms of constituent particles, entropy is a measure of the number of possible microscopic states (or microstates) of a system in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Entropy is often loosely associated with the amount of order or disorder, or of chaos, in a thermodynamic system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The traditional qualitative description of entropy is that it refers to changes in the state of the system and is a measure of "molecular disorder" and the amount of wasted energy in a dynamical energy transformation from one state or form to another.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] In this direction, several recent authors have derived exact entropy formulas to account for and measure disorder and order in atomic and molecular assemblies.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] One of the simpler entropy order/disorder formulas is that derived in 1984 by thermodynamic physicist Peter Landsberg, based on a combination of thermodynamics and information theory arguments.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The concept of entropy can be described qualitatively as a measure of energy dispersal at a specific temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Ambiguities in the terms *disorder* and *chaos*, which usually have meanings directly opposed to equilibrium, contribute to widespread confusion and hamper comprehension of entropy for most students.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] As the second law of thermodynamics shows, in an isolated system internal portions at different temperatures tend to adjust to a single uniform temperature and thus produce equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Physical chemist Peter Atkins, in his textbook *Physical Chemistry*, introduces entropy with the statement that "spontaneous changes are always accompanied by a dispersal of energy or matter and often both".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] It is possible (in a thermal context) to regard lower entropy as a measure of the *effectiveness* or *usefulness* of a particular quantity of energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Energy supplied at a higher temperature (i.e. with low entropy) tends to be more useful than the same amount of energy available at a lower temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Mixing a hot parcel of a fluid with a cold one produces a parcel of intermediate temperature, in which the overall increase in entropy represents a "loss" that can never be replaced.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] As the entropy of the universe is steadily increasing, its total energy is becoming less useful.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Eventually, this is theorised to lead to the heat death of the universe.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] A definition of entropy based entirely on the relation of adiabatic accessibility between equilibrium states was given by E.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] This approach has several predecessors, including the pioneering work of Constantin Carathéodory from 1909 and the monograph by R.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] An equivalent approach that extends the operational definition of entropy to the entire nonequilibrium domain was derived from a rigorous formulation of the general axiomatic foundations of thermodynamics by J.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] In the setting of Lieb and Yngvason, one starts by picking, for a unit amount of the substance under consideration, two reference states ${\textstyle X_{0}}$ and ${\textstyle X_{1}}$ such that the latter is adiabatically accessible from the former but not conversely.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Von Neumann established a rigorous mathematical framework for quantum mechanics with his work *Mathematische Grundlagen der Quantenmechanik*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] He provided in this work a theory of measurement, where the usual notion of wave function collapse is described as an irreversible process (the so-called von Neumann or projective measurement).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Using this concept, in conjunction with the density matrix he extended the classical concept of entropy into the quantum domain.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] When viewed in terms of information theory, the entropy state function is the amount of information in the system that is needed to fully specify the microstate of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Entropy is the measure of the amount of missing information before reception.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Often called *Shannon entropy*, it was originally devised by Claude Shannon in 1948 to study the size of information of a transmitted message.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The definition of information entropy is expressed in terms of a discrete set of probabilities ${\textstyle p_{i}}$ so that: $H(X)=-\sum _{i=1}^{n}{p(x_{i})\log {p(x_{i})}}$ where the base of the logarithm determines the units (for example, the binary logarithm corresponds to bits).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] In the case of transmitted messages, these probabilities were the probabilities that a particular message was actually transmitted, and the entropy of the message system was a measure of the average size of information of a message.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] For the case of equal probabilities (i.e. each message is equally probable), the Shannon entropy (in bits) is just the number of binary questions needed to determine the content of the message.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Most researchers consider information entropy and thermodynamic entropy directly linked to the same concept, while others argue that they are distinct.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Both expressions are mathematically similar.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] If ${\textstyle W}$ is the number of microstates that can yield a given macrostate, and each microstate has the same *a priori* probability, then that probability is ${\textstyle p=1/W}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Some authors argue for dropping the word entropy for the ${\textstyle H}$ function of information theory and using Shannon's other term, "uncertainty", instead.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The entropy of a substance can be measured, although in an indirect way.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The process of measurement goes as follows.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] First, a sample of the substance is cooled as close to absolute zero as possible.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] At such temperatures, the entropy approaches zero – due to the definition of temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Then, small amounts of heat are introduced into the sample and the change in temperature is recorded, until the temperature reaches a desired value (usually 25 °C).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The obtained data allows the user to integrate the equation above, yielding the absolute value of entropy of the substance at the final temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] This value of entropy is called calorimetric entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Although the concept of entropy was originally a thermodynamic concept, it has been adapted in other fields of study, including information theory, psychodynamics, thermoeconomics/ecological economics, and evolution.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Entropy is the only quantity in the physical sciences that seems to imply a particular direction of progress, sometimes called an arrow of time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] As time progresses, the second law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of an isolated system never decreases in large systems over significant periods of time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Hence, from this perspective, entropy measurement is thought of as a clock in these conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Since the 19th century, a number of philosophers have drawn upon the concept of entropy to develop novel metaphysical and ethical systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Examples of this work can be found in the thought of Friedrich Nietzsche and Philipp Mainländer, Claude Lévi-Strauss, Isabelle Stengers, Shannon Mussett, and Drew M.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Chiavazzo et al. proposed that where cave spiders choose to lay their eggs can be explained through entropy minimisation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Entropy has been proven useful in the analysis of base pair sequences in DNA.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Assuming that a finite universe is an isolated system, the second law of thermodynamics states that its total entropy is continually increasing.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] It has been speculated, since the 19th century, that the universe is fated to a heat death in which all the energy ends up as a homogeneous distribution of thermal energy so that no more work can be extracted from any source.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] If the universe can be considered to have generally increasing entropy, then – as Roger Penrose has pointed out – gravity plays an important role in the increase because gravity causes dispersed matter to accumulate into stars, which collapse eventually into black holes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The entropy of a black hole is proportional to the surface area of the black hole's event horizon.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Jacob Bekenstein and Stephen Hawking have shown that black holes have the maximum possible entropy of any object of equal size.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] This makes them likely end points of all entropy-increasing processes, if they are totally effective matter and energy traps.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] However, the escape of energy from black holes might be possible due to quantum activity (see Hawking radiation).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The role of entropy in cosmology remains a controversial subject since the time of Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Recent work has cast some doubt on the heat death hypothesis and the applicability of any simple thermodynamic model to the universe in general.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Although entropy does increase in the model of an expanding universe, the maximum possible entropy rises much more rapidly, moving the universe further from the heat death with time, not closer.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] This results in an "entropy gap" pushing the system further away from the posited heat death equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Other complicating factors, such as the energy density of the vacuum and macroscopic quantum effects, are difficult to reconcile with thermodynamical models, making any predictions of large-scale thermodynamics extremely difficult.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] Current theories suggest the entropy gap to have been originally opened up by the early rapid exponential expansion of the universe.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/entropy-p02] The concept of entropy has been used by Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen in ecological economics, where he coined the term 'entropy pessimism'.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] It also provides a necessary condition for processes such as chemical reactions that may occur under these conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The Gibbs free energy change ( $\Delta G=\Delta H-T\,\Delta S$ , measured in joules in SI) is the *maximum* amount of non-volume expansion work that can be extracted from a closed system (one that can exchange heat and work with its surroundings, but not matter) at fixed temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This maximum can be attained only in a completely reversible process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] When a system transforms reversibly from an initial state to a final state under these conditions, the decrease in Gibbs free energy equals the work done by the system to its surroundings, minus the work of the pressure forces.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The Gibbs energy is the thermodynamic potential that is minimized when a system reaches chemical equilibrium at constant pressure and temperature when not driven by an applied electrolytic voltage.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Its derivative with respect to the reaction coordinate of the system then vanishes at the equilibrium point.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] As such, a reduction in G is necessary for a reaction to be spontaneous under these conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The concept of Gibbs free energy, originally called *available energy*, was developed in the 1870s by the American scientist Josiah Willard Gibbs.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The initial state of the body, according to Gibbs, is supposed to be such that "the body can be made to pass from it to states of dissipated energy by reversible processes".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In his 1876 magnum opus *On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances*, a graphical analysis of multi-phase chemical systems, he engaged his thoughts on chemical-free energy in full.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] If the reactants and products are all in their thermodynamic standard states, then the defining equation is written as $\Delta G^{\circ }=\Delta H^{\circ }-T\,\Delta S^{\circ }$ , where H is enthalpy, T is absolute temperature, and S is entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] According to the second law of thermodynamics, for systems reacting at fixed temperature and pressure without input of non-*Pressure Volume* ( $pV$ ) work, there is a general natural tendency to achieve a minimum of the Gibbs free energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] A quantitative measure of the favorability of a given reaction under these conditions is the change $\Delta G$ in Gibbs free energy that is (or would be) caused by the reaction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] If analysis indicates a positive $\Delta G$ for a reaction, then energy — in the form of electrical or other non- $pV$ work — would have to be added to the reacting system for $\Delta G$ to be smaller than the non- $pV$ work and make it possible for the reaction to occur.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] One can think of $\Delta G$ as the amount of "free" or "useful" energy available to do non- $pV$ work at constant temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The equation can be also seen from the perspective of the system taken together with its surroundings (the rest of the universe).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] First, one assumes that the given reaction at constant temperature and pressure is the only one that is occurring.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Then the entropy released or absorbed by the system equals the entropy that the environment must absorb or release, respectively.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The reaction will only be allowed if the total entropy change of the universe is zero or positive.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This is reflected in a negative $\Delta G$ , and the reaction is called an exergonic process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] If two chemical reactions are coupled, then an otherwise endergonic reaction (one with positive $\Delta G$ ) can be made to happen.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In traditional use, the term "free" was included in "Gibbs free energy" to mean "available in the form of useful work".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The characterization becomes more precise if we add the qualification that it is the energy available for non-pressure-volume work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] (An analogous, but slightly different, meaning of "free" applies in conjunction with the Helmholtz free energy, for systems at constant temperature).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] However, an increasing number of books and journal articles do not include the attachment "free", referring to G as simply "Gibbs energy".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This is the result of a 1988 IUPAC meeting to set unified terminologies for the international scientific community, in which the removal of the adjective "free" was recommended.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This standard, however, has not yet been universally adopted.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The name "free enthalpy" was also used for G in the past.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The quantity called "free energy" is a more advanced and accurate replacement for the outdated term *affinity*, which was used by chemists in the earlier years of physical chemistry to describe the *force* that caused chemical reactions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In this description, as used by Gibbs, $\epsilon$ refers to the internal energy of the body, $\eta$ refers to the entropy of the body, and v is the volume of the body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Thereafter, in 1882, the German scientist Hermann von Helmholtz characterized the affinity as the largest quantity of work which can be gained when the reaction is carried out in a reversible manner, e.g., electrical work in a reversible cell.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Thus, G or F is the amount of energy "free" for work under the given conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Until this point, the general view had been such that: "all chemical reactions drive the system to a state of equilibrium in which the affinities of the reactions vanish".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Over the next 60 years, the term affinity came to be replaced with the term free energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] According to chemistry historian Henry Leicester, the influential 1923 textbook *Thermodynamics and the Free Energy of Chemical Substances* by Gilbert N.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Lewis and Merle Randall led to the replacement of the term "affinity" by the term "free energy" in much of the English-speaking world.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This is one form of the **Gibbs fundamental equation**.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In the infinitesimal expression, the term involving the chemical potential accounts for changes in Gibbs free energy resulting from an influx or outflux of particles.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In other words, it holds for an open system or for a closed, chemically reacting system where the $N_{i}$ are changing.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] For a closed, non-reacting system, this term may be dropped.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Any number of extra terms may be added, depending on the particular system being considered.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Aside from mechanical work, a system may, in addition, perform numerous other types of work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] For example, in the infinitesimal expression, the contractile work energy associated with a thermodynamic system that is a contractile fiber that shortens by an amount $-\mathrm {d} l$ under a force f would result in a term $f\,\mathrm {d} l$ being added.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] If a quantity of charge $-\mathrm {d} e$ is acquired by a system at an electrical potential $\Psi$ , the electrical work associated with this is $-\Psi \,\mathrm {d} e$ , which would be included in the infinitesimal expression.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Other work terms are added on per system requirements.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Each quantity in the equations above can be divided by the amount of substance, measured in moles, to form *molar Gibbs free energy*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The Gibbs free energy is one of the most important thermodynamic functions for the characterization of a system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] It is a factor in determining outcomes such as the voltage of an electrochemical cell, and the equilibrium constant for a reversible reaction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In isothermal, isobaric systems, Gibbs free energy can be thought of as a "dynamic" quantity, in that it is a representative measure of the competing effects of the enthalpic and entropic driving forces involved in a thermodynamic process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In non-ideal systems, fugacity comes into play.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The Gibbs free energy total differential with respect to natural variables may be derived by Legendre transforms of the internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The natural variables of G are then p , T , and $\left\{N_{i}\right\}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Because some of the natural variables of G are intensive, $\mathrm {d} G$ may not be integrated using Euler relations as is the case with internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This result shows that the chemical potential of a substance i is its (partial) molecular Gibbs free energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] It applies to homogeneous, macroscopic systems, but not to all thermodynamic systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The system under consideration is held at constant temperature and pressure, and is closed (no matter can come in or out).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] where $\delta Q$ is energy added as heat, and $\delta W$ is energy added as work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The work done on the system may be written as $\delta W=-p\,\mathrm {d} V+\delta W_{x}$ , where $-p\,\mathrm {d} V$ is the mechanical work of compression/expansion done on or by the system and $\delta W_{x}$ is all other forms of work, which may include electrical, magnetic, etc.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This means that for such a system when not in equilibrium, the Gibbs energy will always be decreasing, and in equilibrium, the infinitesimal change $\mathrm {d} G$ will be zero.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In particular, this will be true if the system is experiencing any number of internal chemical reactions on its path to equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] where S is the entropy, V is the system volume, p is its pressure and T is its absolute temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The combination ( ${\mathcal {E}}$ , $Q_{\mathrm {ele} }$ ) is an example of a conjugate pair of variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] At constant pressure the above equation produces a Maxwell relation that links the change in open cell voltage with temperature T (a measurable quantity) to the change in entropy S when charge is passed isothermally and isobarically.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The latter is closely related to the reaction entropy of the electrochemical reaction that lends the battery its power.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] where $n_{0}$ is the number of electrons/ion, and $F_{0}$ is the Faraday constant, and the minus sign indicates discharge of the cell.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] where $\Delta H$ is the enthalpy of reaction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The quantities on the right are all directly measurable.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] which relates the equilibrium constant with Gibbs free energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] This implies that at equilibrium, $Q_{\mathrm {r} }=K_{\mathrm {eq} }$ and $\Delta _{\mathrm {r} }G=0$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] The standard Gibbs free energy of formation of a compound is the change of Gibbs free energy that accompanies the formation of 1 mol of that substance from its component elements, in their standard states (the most stable form of the element at 25 °C and 100 kPa).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Its symbol is $\Delta _{\mathrm {f} }G^{\circ }$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] All elements in their standard states (diatomic oxygen gas, graphite, etc.) have standard Gibbs free energy change of formation equal to zero, as there is no change involved.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] where $Q_{\mathrm {f} }$ is the reaction quotient.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] where K is the equilibrium constant of the formation reaction of the substance from the elements in their standard states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Gibbs free energy was originally defined graphically.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In 1873, American scientist Willard Gibbs published his first thermodynamics paper, "Graphical Methods in the Thermodynamics of Fluids", in which Gibbs used the two coordinates of the entropy and volume to represent the state of the body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In his second follow-up paper, "A Method of Geometrical Representation of the Thermodynamic Properties of Substances by Means of Surfaces", published later that year, Gibbs added in the third coordinate of the energy of the body, defined on three figures.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] In 1874, Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell used Gibbs' figures to make a 3D energy-entropy-volume thermodynamic surface of a fictitious water-like substance.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/gibbs-free-energy] Thus, in order to understand the concept of Gibbs free energy, it may help to understand its interpretation by Gibbs as section AB on his figure 3, and as Maxwell sculpted that section on his 3D surface figure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The corresponding intensive property is the specific heat capacity, found by dividing the heat capacity of an object by its mass.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Dividing the heat capacity by the amount of substance in moles yields its molar heat capacity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The volumetric heat capacity measures the heat capacity per volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In architecture and civil engineering, the heat capacity of a building is often referred to as its *thermal mass*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity of an object, denoted by C , is the limit $C=\lim _{\Delta T\to 0}{\frac {Q}{\Delta T}},$ where Q is the amount of heat that must be added to the object (of mass *M*) in order to raise its temperature by $\Delta T$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The value of this parameter usually varies considerably depending on the starting temperature T of the object and the pressure p applied to it.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In particular, it typically varies dramatically with phase transitions such as melting or vaporization (see enthalpy of fusion and enthalpy of vaporization).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Therefore, it is considered a function $C(p,T)$ of those two variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The variation can be ignored in contexts when working with objects in narrow ranges of temperature and pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] For example, the heat capacity of a block of iron weighing one pound is about 204 J/K when measured from a starting temperature *T* = 25 °C and *P* = 1 atm of pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] That approximate value is adequate for temperatures between 15 °C and 35 °C, and surrounding pressures from 0 to 10 atmospheres, because the exact value varies very little in those ranges.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] One can trust that the same heat input of 204 J will raise the temperature of the block from 15 °C to 16 °C, or from 34 °C to 35 °C, with negligible error.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] At constant pressure, heat supplied to the system contributes to both the work done and the change in internal energy, according to the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] where the final equality follows from the appropriate Maxwell relations, and is commonly used as the definition of the isobaric heat capacity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] A system undergoing a process at constant volume implies that no expansion work is done, so the heat supplied contributes only to the change in internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity obtained this way is denoted $C_{V}.$ The value of $C_{V}$ is always less than the value of $C_{p}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] where $N_{f}$ is the number of degrees of freedom of each individual particle in the gas, and $N_{i}=N_{f}-3$ is the number of internal degrees of freedom, where the number 3 comes from the three translational degrees of freedom (for a gas in 3D space).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] This means that a monoatomic ideal gas (with zero internal degrees of freedom) will have isochoric heat capacity $C_{v}={\frac {3nR}{2}}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Heat capacity of a system undergoing phase transition is infinite, because the heat is utilized in changing the state of the material rather than raising the overall temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Given an isochoric system, $C_{v}=\left({\frac {\partial U}{\partial T}}\right)_{N,V}$ , which can be rewritten as $\left.dU\right|_{N,V=const}=C_{v}dT$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity may be well-defined even for heterogeneous objects, with separate parts made of different materials; such as an electric motor, a crucible with some metal, or a whole building.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In many cases, the (isobaric) heat capacity of such objects can be computed by simply adding together the (isobaric) heat capacities of the individual parts.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] However, this computation is valid only when all parts of the object are at the same external pressure before and after the measurement.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] For example, when heating an amount of gas in an elastic container, its volume *and pressure* will both increase, even if the atmospheric pressure outside the container is kept constant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Therefore, the effective heat capacity of the gas, in that situation, will have a value intermediate between its isobaric and isochoric capacities $C_{p}$ and $C_{V}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The heat energy that is supplied may end up as kinetic energy (energy of motion) and potential energy (energy stored in force fields), both at macroscopic and atomic scales.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Then the change in temperature will depend on the particular path that the system followed through its phase space between the initial and final states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Namely, one must somehow specify how the positions, velocities, pressures, volumes, etc. changed between the initial and final states; and use the general tools of thermodynamics to predict the system's reaction to a small energy input.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The "constant volume" and "constant pressure" heating modes are just two among infinitely many paths that a simple homogeneous system can follow.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity can usually be measured by the method implied by its definition: start with the object at a known uniform temperature, add a known amount of heat energy to it, wait for its temperature to become uniform, and measure the change in its temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] This method can give moderately accurate values for many solids; however, it cannot provide very precise measurements, especially for gases.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The SI unit for heat capacity of an object is joule per kelvin (J/K or J⋅K−1).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Since an increment of temperature of one degree Celsius is the same as an increment of one kelvin, that is the same unit as J/°C.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The heat capacity of an object is an amount of energy divided by a temperature change, which has the dimension L2⋅M⋅T−2⋅Θ−1.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Therefore, the SI unit J/K is equivalent to kilogram meter squared per second squared per kelvin (kg⋅m2⋅s−2⋅K−1 ).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In those contexts, the unit of heat capacity is 1 BTU/°R ≈ 1900 J/K.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] The BTU was in fact defined so that the average heat capacity of one pound of water would be 1 BTU/°F.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In this regard, with respect to mass, note conversion of 1 Btu/lb⋅°R ≈ 4,187 J/kg⋅K and the calorie (below).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In chemistry, heat amounts are often measured in calories.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Most physical systems exhibit a positive heat capacity; constant-volume and constant-pressure heat capacities, rigorously defined as partial derivatives, are always positive for homogeneous bodies.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] However, even though it can seem paradoxical at first, there are some systems for which the heat capacity $Q/\Delta T$ is *negative*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Examples include a reversibly and nearly adiabatically expanding ideal gas, which cools, $\Delta T<0$ , while a small amount of heat $Q>0$ is put in, or combusting methane with increasing temperature, $\Delta T>0$ , and giving off heat, $Q<0$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Others are inhomogeneous systems that do not meet the strict definition of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] They include gravitating objects such as stars and galaxies, and also some nano-scale clusters of a few tens of atoms close to a phase transition.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] A negative heat capacity can result in a negative temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] If the system loses energy, for example, by radiating energy into space, the average kinetic energy actually increases.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] If a temperature is defined by the average kinetic energy, then the system therefore can be said to have a negative heat capacity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] A more extreme version of this occurs with black holes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] According to black-hole thermodynamics, the more mass and energy a black hole absorbs, the colder it becomes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In contrast, if it is a net emitter of energy, through Hawking radiation, it will become hotter and hotter until it boils away.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] According to the second law of thermodynamics, when two systems with different temperatures interact via a purely thermal connection, heat will flow from the hotter system to the cooler one (this can also be understood from a statistical point of view).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Therefore, if such systems have equal temperatures, they are at thermal equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] However, this equilibrium is stable only if the systems have *positive* heat capacities.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] For such systems, when heat flows from a higher-temperature system to a lower-temperature one, the temperature of the first decreases and that of the latter increases, so that both approach equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] In contrast, for systems with *negative* heat capacities, the temperature of the hotter system will further increase as it loses heat, and that of the colder will further decrease, so that they will move farther from equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] This means that the equilibrium is unstable.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] For example, according to theory, the smaller (less massive) a black hole is, the smaller its Schwarzschild radius will be, and therefore the greater the curvature of its event horizon will be, as well as its temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/heat-capacity] Thus, the smaller the black hole, the more thermal radiation it will emit and the more quickly it will evaporate by Hawking radiation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The **second law of thermodynamics** is a physical law based on universal empirical observation concerning heat and energy interconversions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A simple statement of the law is that heat always flows spontaneously from hotter to colder regions of matter (or 'downhill' in terms of the temperature gradient).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Another statement is: "Not all heat can be converted into work in a cyclic process." These are informal definitions, however; more formal definitions appear below.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law of thermodynamics establishes the concept of entropy as a physical property of a thermodynamic system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It predicts whether processes are forbidden despite obeying the requirement of conservation of energy as expressed in the first law of thermodynamics and provides necessary criteria for spontaneous processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For example, the first law allows the process of a cup falling off a table and breaking on the floor, as well as allowing the reverse process of the cup fragments coming back together and 'jumping' back onto the table, while the second law allows the former and denies the latter.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law may be formulated by the observation that the entropy of isolated systems left to spontaneous evolution cannot decrease, as they always tend toward a state of thermodynamic equilibrium where the entropy is highest at the given internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] An increase in the combined entropy of system and surroundings accounts for the irreversibility of natural processes, often referred to in the concept of the arrow of time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Historically, the second law was an empirical finding that was accepted as an axiom of thermodynamic theory.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Statistical mechanics provides a microscopic explanation of the law in terms of probability distributions of the states of large assemblies of atoms or molecules.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law has been expressed in many ways.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Its first formulation, which preceded the proper definition of entropy and was based on caloric theory, is Carnot's theorem, formulated by the French scientist Sadi Carnot, who in 1824 showed that the efficiency of conversion of heat to work in a heat engine has an upper limit.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The first rigorous definition of the second law based on the concept of entropy came from German scientist Rudolf Clausius in the 1850s and included his statement that heat can never pass from a colder to a warmer body without some other change, connected therewith, occurring at the same time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law of thermodynamics allows the definition of the concept of thermodynamic temperature, but this has been formally delegated to the zeroth law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The first law of thermodynamics provides the definition of the internal energy of a thermodynamic system, and expresses its change for a closed system in terms of work and heat.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It can be linked to the law of conservation of energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Conceptually, the first law describes the fundamental principle that systems do not consume or 'use up' energy, that energy is neither created nor destroyed, but is simply converted from one form to another.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law is concerned with the direction of natural processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It asserts that a natural process runs only in one sense, and is not reversible.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] That is, the state of a natural system itself can be reversed, but not without increasing the entropy of the system's surroundings, that is, both the state of the system plus the state of its surroundings cannot be together, fully reversed, without implying the destruction of entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For example, when a path for conduction or radiation is made available, heat always flows spontaneously from a hotter to a colder body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Such phenomena are accounted for in terms of entropy change.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A heat pump can reverse this heat flow, but the reversal process and the original process, both cause entropy production, thereby increasing the entropy of the system's surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Different notations are used for an infinitesimal amount of heat $(\delta )$ and infinitesimal change of entropy $(\mathrm {d} )$ because entropy is a function of state, while heat, like work, is not.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] which is the basis of the accurate determination of the absolute entropy of pure substances from measured heat capacity curves and entropy changes at phase transitions, i.e. by calorimetry.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The zeroth law of thermodynamics in its usual short statement allows recognition that two bodies in a relation of thermal equilibrium have the same temperature, especially that a test body has the same temperature as a reference thermometric body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For a body in thermal equilibrium with another, there are indefinitely many empirical temperature scales, in general respectively depending on the properties of a particular reference thermometric body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law allows a distinguished temperature scale, which defines an absolute, thermodynamic temperature, independent of the properties of any particular reference thermometric body.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law of thermodynamics may be expressed in many specific ways, the most prominent classical statements being the statement by Rudolf Clausius (1854), the statement by Lord Kelvin (1851), and the statement in axiomatic thermodynamics by Constantin Carathéodory (1909).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] These statements cast the law in general physical terms citing the impossibility of certain processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The Clausius and the Kelvin statements have been shown to be equivalent.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The historical origin of the second law of thermodynamics was in Sadi Carnot's theoretical analysis of the flow of heat in steam engines (1824).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It represents the theoretical maximum efficiency of a heat engine operating between any two given thermal or heat reservoirs at different temperatures.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Carnot's principle was recognized by Carnot at a time when the caloric theory represented the dominant understanding of the nature of heat, before the recognition of the first law of thermodynamics, and before the mathematical expression of the concept of entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Interpreted in the light of the first law, Carnot's analysis is physically equivalent to the second law of thermodynamics, and remains valid today.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In 1850, the German scientist Rudolf Clausius laid the foundation for the second law of thermodynamics by examining the relation between heat transfer and work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The statement by Clausius uses the concept of 'passage of heat'.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] As is usual in thermodynamic discussions, this means 'net transfer of energy as heat', and does not refer to contributory transfers one way and the other.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Heat cannot spontaneously flow from cold regions to hot regions without external work being performed on the system, which is evident from ordinary experience of refrigeration, for example.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In a refrigerator, heat is transferred from cold to hot, but only when forced by an external agent, the refrigeration system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Understanding the Clausius statement requires prior definition of the concepts of 'hot versus cold' (temperature) and 'heat' (heat interaction).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Lord Kelvin expressed the second law in several wordings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The Kelvin–Planck statement does not rule out the possibility of a system developing a net amount of work from a heat transfer drawn from a single reservoir.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It only denies this possibility if the system undergoes a thermodynamic cycle.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Suppose there is an engine violating the Kelvin statement: i.e., one that drains heat and converts it completely into work (the drained heat is fully converted to work) in a cyclic fashion without any other result.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Now pair it with a reversed Carnot engine as shown by the right figure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The efficiency of a normal heat engine is *η* and so the efficiency of the reversed heat engine is 1/*η*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The net and sole effect of the combined pair of engines is to transfer heat ${\textstyle \Delta Q=Q\left({\frac {1}{\eta }}-1\right)}$ from the cooler reservoir to the hotter one, which violates the Clausius statement.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Thus a violation of the Kelvin statement implies a violation of the Clausius statement, i.e. the Clausius statement implies the Kelvin statement.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] We can prove in a similar manner that the Kelvin statement implies the Clausius statement, and hence the two are equivalent.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Planck offered the following proposition as derived directly from experience.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This is sometimes regarded as his statement of the second law, but he regarded it as a starting point for the derivation of the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It is almost customary in textbooks to speak of the "Kelvin–Planck statement" of the law, as for example in the text by ter Haar and Wergeland.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Max Planck stated the second law as follows.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Rather like Planck's statement is that of George Uhlenbeck and G.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Constantin Carathéodory formulated thermodynamics on a purely mathematical axiomatic foundation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] With this formulation, he described the concept of adiabatic accessibility for the first time and provided the foundation for a new subfield of classical thermodynamics, often called geometrical thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It follows from Carathéodory's principle that quantity of energy quasi-statically transferred as heat is a holonomic process function, in other words, $\delta Q=TdS$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Though it is almost customary in textbooks to say that Carathéodory's principle expresses the second law and to treat it as equivalent to the Clausius or to the Kelvin-Planck statements, such is not the case.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] To get all the content of the second law, Carathéodory's principle needs to be supplemented by Planck's principle, that isochoric work always increases the internal energy of a closed system that was initially in its own internal thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In 1926, Max Planck wrote an important paper on the basics of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This formulation does not mention heat and does not mention temperature, nor even entropy, and does not necessarily implicitly rely on those concepts, but it implies the content of the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Not mentioning entropy, this principle of Planck is stated in physical terms.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It is very closely related to the Kelvin statement given just above.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It is relevant that for a system at constant volume and mole numbers, the entropy is a monotonic function of the internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Nevertheless, this principle of Planck is not actually Planck's preferred statement of the second law, which is quoted above, in a previous sub-section of the present section of this present article, and relies on the concept of entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A statement that in a sense is complementary to Planck's principle is made by Claus Borgnakke and Richard E.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Differing from Planck's just foregoing principle, this one is explicitly in terms of entropy change.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Removal of matter from a system can also decrease its entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Hatsopoulos and Joseph Keenan published their textbook *Principles of General Thermodynamics*, which restates the second law of thermodynamics in terms of the existence of stable equilibrium states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This shows that the second law of thermodynamics can be stated in terms of the existence of stable equilibrium states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The Hatsopoulos-Keenan statement of the Second Law entails the Clausius, Kelvin-Planck, and Carathéodory statements of the Second Law, and has provided a basis to extend the traditional definition of entropy to the non-equilibrium domain.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Hatsopoulus and Keenan maintained that it is unlikely to identify a satisfactory definition of heat without a prior statement of the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The Hatsopoulos–Keenan statement of the second law has been developed into a rigorous formulation of the general axiomatic foundations of equilibrium and nonequilibrium, classical, statistical, and quantum thermodynamics by G.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law has been shown to be equivalent to the internal energy *U* defined as a convex function of the other extensive properties of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] That is, when a system is described by stating its internal energy *U*, an extensive variable, as a function of its entropy *S*, volume *V*, and mol number *N*, i.e.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The Clausius inequality, as well as some other statements of the second law, must be re-stated to have general applicability for all forms of heat transfer, i.e. scenarios involving radiative fluxes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For example, the integrand (đ*Q*/*T*) of the Clausius expression applies to heat conduction and convection, and the case of ideal infinitesimal blackbody radiation (BR) transfer, but does not apply to most radiative transfer scenarios and in some cases has no physical meaning whatsoever.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Consequently, the Clausius inequality was re-stated so that it is applicable to cycles with processes involving any form of heat transfer.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The entropy transfer with radiative fluxes ( $\delta S_{\text{NetRad}}$ ) is taken separately from that due to heat transfer by conduction and convection ( $\delta Q_{CC}$ ), where the temperature is evaluated at the system boundary where the heat transfer occurs.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In a nutshell, the Clausius inequality is saying that when a cycle is completed, the change in the state property S will be zero, so the entropy that was produced during the cycle must have transferred out of the system by heat transfer.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The $\delta$ (or đ) indicates a path dependent integration.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Due to the inherent emission of radiation from all matter, most entropy flux calculations involve incident, reflected and emitted radiative fluxes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In deriving this blackbody spectral entropy radiance, with the goal of deriving the blackbody energy formula, Planck postulated that the energy of a photon was quantized (partly to simplify the mathematics), thereby starting quantum theory.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A non-equilibrium statistical mechanics approach has also been used to obtain the same result as Planck, indicating it has wider significance and represents a non-equilibrium entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A plot of *Kv* versus frequency (v) for various values of temperature (T) gives a family of blackbody radiation energy spectra, and likewise for the entropy spectra.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For non-blackbody radiation (NBR) emission fluxes, the spectral entropy radiance *Lv* is found by substituting *Kv* spectral energy radiance data into the *Lv* expression (noting that emitted and reflected entropy fluxes are, in general, not independent).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For the emission of NBR, including graybody radiation (GR), the resultant emitted entropy flux, or radiance L, has a higher ratio of entropy-to-energy (*L*/*K*), than that of BR.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] That is, the entropy flux of NBR emission is farther removed from the conduction and convection *q*/*T* result, than that for BR emission.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] As a result, a conceptual statement of the principle is very useful in engineering analysis.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Thermodynamic systems can be categorized by the four combinations of either entropy (S) up or down, and uniformity (Y) – between system and its environment – up or down.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This 'special' category of processes, category IV, is characterized by movement in the direction of low disorder and low uniformity, counteracting the second law tendency towards uniformity and disorder.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law can be conceptually stated as follows: Matter and energy have the tendency to reach a state of uniformity or internal and external equilibrium, a state of maximum disorder (entropy).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Real non-equilibrium processes always produce entropy, causing increased disorder in the universe, while idealized reversible processes produce no entropy and no process is known to exist that destroys entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The tendency of a system to approach uniformity may be counteracted, and the system may become more ordered or complex, by the combination of two things, a work or exergy source and some form of instruction or intelligence.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Where 'exergy' is the thermal, mechanical, electric or chemical work potential of an energy source or flow, and 'instruction or intelligence', although subjective, is in the context of the set of category IV processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Consider a category IV example of robotic manufacturing and assembly of vehicles in a factory.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The robotic machinery requires electrical work input and instructions, but when completed, the manufactured products have less uniformity with their surroundings, or more complexity (higher order) relative to the raw materials they were made from.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Thus, system entropy or disorder decreases while the tendency towards uniformity between the system and its environment is counteracted.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In this example, the instructions, as well as the source of work may be internal or external to the system, and they may or may not cross the system boundary.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] To illustrate, the instructions may be pre-coded and the electrical work may be stored in an energy storage system on-site.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Alternatively, the control of the machinery may be by remote operation over a communications network, while the electric work is supplied to the factory from the local electric grid.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In addition, humans may directly play, in whole or in part, the role that the robotic machinery plays in manufacturing.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In this case, instructions may be involved, but intelligence is either directly responsible, or indirectly responsible, for the direction or application of work in such a way as to counteract the tendency towards disorder and uniformity.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] There are also situations where the entropy spontaneously decreases by means of energy and entropy transfer.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] When thermodynamic constraints are not present, spontaneously energy or mass, as well as accompanying entropy, may be transferred out of a system in a progress to reach external equilibrium or uniformity in intensive properties of the system with its surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This occurs spontaneously because the energy or mass transferred from the system to its surroundings results in a higher entropy in the surroundings, that is, it results in higher overall entropy of the system plus its surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Note that this transfer of entropy requires dis-equilibrium in properties, such as a temperature difference.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] One example of this is the cooling crystallization of water that can occur when the system's surroundings are below freezing temperatures.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Unconstrained heat transfer can spontaneously occur, leading to water molecules freezing into a crystallized structure of reduced disorder (sticking together in a certain order due to molecular attraction).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The entropy of the system decreases, but the system approaches uniformity with its surroundings (category III).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] On the other hand, consider the refrigeration of water in a warm environment.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Due to refrigeration, as heat is extracted from the water, the temperature and entropy of the water decreases, as the system moves further away from uniformity with its warm surroundings or environment (category IV).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The main point, take-away, is that refrigeration not only requires a source of work, it requires designed equipment, as well as pre-coded or direct operational intelligence or instructions to achieve the desired refrigeration effect.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Before the establishment of the second law, many people who were interested in inventing a perpetual motion machine had tried to circumvent the restrictions of first law of thermodynamics by extracting the massive internal energy of the environment as the power of the machine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Such a machine is called a "perpetual motion machine of the second kind".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law declared the impossibility of such machines.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Carnot's theorem (1824) is a principle that limits the maximum efficiency for any possible engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The efficiency solely depends on the temperature difference between the hot and cold thermal reservoirs.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In his ideal model, the heat of caloric converted into work could be reinstated by reversing the motion of the cycle, a concept subsequently known as thermodynamic reversibility.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Carnot, however, further postulated that some caloric is lost, not being converted to mechanical work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Hence, no real heat engine could realize the Carnot cycle's reversibility and was condemned to be less efficient.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Though formulated in terms of caloric (see the obsolete caloric theory), rather than entropy, this was an early insight into the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The equality holds in the reversible case and the strict inequality holds in the irreversible case, with *T*surr as the temperature of the heat bath (surroundings) here.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The reversible case is used to introduce the state function entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This is because in cyclic processes the variation of a state function is zero from state functionality.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] where *W**n* is the net work done by the engine per cycle, *q*H > 0 is the heat added to the engine from a hot reservoir, and *q*C = −|*q**C*| < 0 is waste heat given off to a cold reservoir from the engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Thus the efficiency depends only on the ratio |*q*C| / |*q*H|.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Carnot's theorem states that all reversible engines operating between the same heat reservoirs are equally efficient.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In addition, a reversible heat engine operating between temperatures *T*1 and *T*3 must have the same efficiency as one consisting of two cycles, one between *T*1 and another (intermediate) temperature *T*2, and the second between *T*2 and *T*3, where *T*1 > *T*2 > *T*3.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This is because, if a part of the two cycle engine is hidden such that it is recognized as an engine between the reservoirs at the temperatures *T*1 and *T*3, then the efficiency of this engine must be same to the other engine at the same reservoirs.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] If we choose engines such that work done by the one cycle engine and the two cycle engine are same, then the efficiency of each heat engine is written as below.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Here, the engine 1 is the one cycle engine, and the engines 2 and 3 make the two cycle engine where there is the intermediate reservoir at *T*2.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] We also have used the fact that the heat $q_{2}$ passes through the intermediate thermal reservoir at $T_{2}$ without losing its energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] (I.e., $q_{2}$ is not lost during its passage through the reservoir at $T_{2}$ .) This fact can be proved by the following.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In order to have the consistency in the last equation, the heat $q_{2}$ flown from the engine 2 to the intermediate reservoir must be equal to the heat $q_{2}^{*}$ flown out from the reservoir to the engine 3.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Now consider the case where $T_{1}$ is a fixed reference temperature: the temperature of the triple point of water as 273.16 K; $T_{1}=\mathrm {273.16~K}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] That means the line integral $\int _{L}{\frac {\delta Q}{T}}$ is path independent for reversible processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] With this we can only obtain the difference of entropy by integrating the above formula.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] To obtain the absolute value, we need the third law of thermodynamics, which states that *S* = 0 at absolute zero for perfect crystals.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For any irreversible process, since entropy is a state function, we can always connect the initial and terminal states with an imaginary reversible process and integrating on that path to calculate the difference in entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Now reverse the reversible process and combine it with the said irreversible process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] where the equality holds if the transformation is reversible.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] If the process is an adiabatic process, then $\delta Q=0$ , so $\Delta S\geq 0$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] An important and revealing idealized special case is to consider applying the second law to the scenario of an isolated system (called the total system or universe), made up of two parts: a sub-system of interest, and the sub-system's surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] where *μ**iR* are the chemical potentials of chemical species in the external surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] where we have first used the definition of entropy in classical thermodynamics (alternatively, in statistical thermodynamics, the relation between entropy change, temperature and absorbed heat can be derived); and then the second law inequality from above.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] i.e. the change in the subsystem's exergy plus the useful work done *by* the subsystem (or, the change in the subsystem's exergy less any work, additional to that done by the pressure reservoir, done *on* the system) must be less than or equal to zero.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In sum, if a proper *infinite-reservoir-like* reference state is chosen as the system surroundings in the real world, then the second law predicts a decrease in *E* for an irreversible process and no change for a reversible process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This expression together with the associated reference state permits a design engineer working at the macroscopic scale (above the thermodynamic limit) to utilize the second law without directly measuring or considering entropy change in a total isolated system (see also *Process engineer*).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Those changes have already been considered by the assumption that the system under consideration can reach equilibrium with the reference state without altering the reference state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] An efficiency for a process or collection of processes that compares it to the reversible ideal may also be found (see *Exergy efficiency*).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This approach to the second law is widely utilized in engineering practice, environmental accounting, systems ecology, and other disciplines.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The second law determines whether a proposed physical or chemical process is forbidden or may occur spontaneously.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For isolated systems, no energy is provided by the surroundings and the second law requires that the entropy of the system alone cannot decrease: Δ*S* ≥ 0.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Mechanical energy can be converted to thermal energy (but not the reverse).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A solute can move from a region of higher concentration to a region of lower concentration (but not the reverse).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] However, for some non-isolated systems which can exchange energy with their surroundings, the surroundings exchange enough heat with the system, or do sufficient work on the system, so that the processes occur in the opposite direction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] In such a case, the reverse process can occur because it is *coupled* to a simultaneous process that *increases* the entropy of the surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The coupled process will go forward provided that the total entropy change of the system and surroundings combined is nonnegative as required by the second law: Δ*S*tot = Δ*S* + Δ*S*R ≥ 0.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Thermal energy can be converted by a heat engine to mechanical work within a system at a single temperature, provided that the heat engine transfers a sufficient amount of heat from the system to a lower-temperature region in the surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] A solute can travel from a region of lower concentration to a region of higher concentration in the biochemical process of active transport, if sufficient work is provided by a concentration gradient of a chemical such as ATP or by an electrochemical gradient.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] For a similar process at constant temperature and volume, the change in Helmholtz free energy must be negative, $\Delta A<0$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Thus, a negative value of the change in free energy (*G* or *A*) is a necessary condition for a process to be spontaneous.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This is the most useful form of the second law of thermodynamics in chemistry, where free-energy changes can be calculated from tabulated enthalpies of formation and standard molar entropies of reactants and products.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The chemical equilibrium condition at constant *T* and *p* without electrical work is d*G* = 0.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The first theory of the conversion of heat into mechanical work is due to Sadi Carnot in 1824.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] He was the first to realize correctly that the efficiency of this conversion depends on the difference of temperature between an engine and its surroundings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Recognizing the significance of James Prescott Joule's work on the conservation of energy, Rudolf Clausius was the first to formulate the second law during 1850, in this form: heat does not flow *spontaneously* from cold to hot bodies.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] While common knowledge now, this was contrary to the caloric theory of heat popular at the time, which considered heat as a fluid.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] From there he was able to infer the principle of Sadi Carnot and the definition of entropy (1865).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Established during the 19th century, the Kelvin–Planck statement of the second law says, "It is impossible for any device that operates on a cycle to receive heat from a single reservoir and produce a net amount of work." This statement was shown to be equivalent to the statement of Clausius.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The ergodic hypothesis is also important for Ludwig Boltzmann's approach.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It says that, over long periods of time, the time spent in some region of the phase space of microstates with the same energy is proportional to the volume of this region, i.e. that all accessible microstates are equally probable over a long period of time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Equivalently, it says that time average and average over the statistical ensemble are the same.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] There is a traditional doctrine, starting with Clausius, that entropy can be understood in terms of molecular 'disorder' within a macroscopic system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] where *Q* is heat, *T* is temperature and *N* is the "equivalence-value" of all uncompensated transformations involved in a cyclical process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Later, in 1865, Clausius would come to define "equivalence-value" as entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This statement is the best-known phrasing of the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Because of the looseness of its language, e.g. universe, as well as lack of specific conditions, e.g. open, closed, or isolated, many people take this simple statement to mean that the second law of thermodynamics applies virtually to every subject imaginable.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] This is not true; this statement is only a simplified version of a more extended and precise description.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The equality sign applies after equilibration.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] with ${\dot {S}}_{\text{i}}\geq 0$ , the sum of the rate of entropy production by all processes inside the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The advantage of this formulation is that it shows the effect of the entropy production.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The rate of entropy production is a very important concept since it determines (limits) the efficiency of thermal machines.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Multiplied with ambient temperature $T_{\text{a}}$ it gives the so-called dissipated energy $P_{\text{diss}}=T_{\text{a}}{\dot {S}}_{\text{i}}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] The equality sign holds in the case that only reversible processes take place inside the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] If irreversible processes take place (which is the case in real systems in operation) the >-sign holds.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] If heat is supplied to the system at several places we have to take the algebraic sum of the corresponding terms.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] Here, ${\dot {S}}$ is the flow of entropy into the system associated with the flow of matter entering the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] It should not be confused with the time derivative of the entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p01] If matter is supplied at several places we have to take the algebraic sum of these contributions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Statistical mechanics gives an explanation for the second law by postulating that a material is composed of atoms and molecules which are in constant motion.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] A particular set of positions and velocities for each particle in the system is called a microstate of the system and because of the constant motion, the system is constantly changing its microstate.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Statistical mechanics postulates that, in equilibrium, each microstate that the system might be in is equally likely to occur, and when this assumption is made, it leads directly to the conclusion that the second law must hold in a statistical sense.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] That is, the second law will hold on average, with a statistical variation on the order of $1/{\sqrt {N}}$ where N is the number of particles in the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] For everyday (macroscopic) situations, the probability that the second law will be violated is practically zero.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] However, for systems with a small number of particles, thermodynamic parameters, including the entropy, may show significant statistical deviations from that predicted by the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Classical thermodynamic theory does not deal with these statistical variations.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Due to Loschmidt's paradox, derivations of the second law have to make an assumption regarding the past, namely that the system is uncorrelated at some time in the past; this allows for simple probabilistic treatment.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This assumption is usually thought as a boundary condition, and thus the second law is ultimately a consequence of the initial conditions somewhere in the past, probably at the beginning of the universe (the Big Bang), though other scenarios have also been suggested.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The first part of the second law, which states that the entropy of a thermally isolated system can only increase, is a trivial consequence of the equal prior probability postulate, if we restrict the notion of the entropy to systems in thermal equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] where $\Omega \left(E\right)$ is the number of quantum states in a small interval between E and $E+\delta E$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Here $\delta E$ is a macroscopically small energy interval that is kept fixed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Strictly speaking this means that the entropy depends on the choice of $\delta E$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] However, in the thermodynamic limit (i.e. in the limit of infinitely large system size), the specific entropy (entropy per unit volume or per unit mass) does not depend on $\delta E$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Suppose we have an isolated system whose macroscopic state is specified by a number of variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] These macroscopic variables can, e.g., refer to the total volume, the positions of pistons in the system, etc.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Then $\Omega$ will depend on the values of these variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Suppose we start from an equilibrium situation and we suddenly remove a constraint on a variable.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Then right after we do this, there are a number $\Omega$ of accessible microstates, but equilibrium has not yet been reached, so the actual probabilities of the system being in some accessible state are not yet equal to the prior probability of $1/\Omega$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] We have already seen that in the final equilibrium state, the entropy will have increased or have stayed the same relative to the previous equilibrium state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Boltzmann's H-theorem, however, proves that the quantity *H* increases monotonically as a function of time during the intermediate out of equilibrium state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] See *Microcanonical ensemble* for the justification for this definition.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Suppose that the system has some external parameter, *x*, that can be changed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] In general, the energy eigenstates of the system will depend on *x*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] According to the adiabatic theorem of quantum mechanics, in the limit of an infinitely slow change of the system's Hamiltonian, the system will stay in the same energy eigenstate and thus change its energy according to the change in energy of the energy eigenstate it is in.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The generalized force, *X*, corresponding to the external variable *x* is defined such that $Xdx$ is the work performed by the system if *x* is increased by an amount *dx*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] For example, if *x* is the volume, then *X* is the pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] To evaluate the average, we partition the $\Omega \left(E\right)$ energy eigenstates by counting how many of them have a value for ${\frac {dE_{r}}{dx}}$ within a range between Y and $Y+\delta Y$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] We can relate this to the derivative of the entropy with respect to *x* at constant energy *E* as follows.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Then $\Omega \left(E\right)$ will change because the energy eigenstates depend on *x*, causing energy eigenstates to move into or out of the range between E and $E+\delta E$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Let's focus again on the energy eigenstates for which ${\textstyle {\frac {dE_{r}}{dx}}}$ lies within the range between Y and $Y+\delta Y$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Since these energy eigenstates increase in energy by *Y dx*, all such energy eigenstates that are in the interval ranging from *E* – *Y* *dx* to *E* move from below *E* to above *E*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] If $Ydx\leq \delta E$ , all these energy eigenstates will move into the range between E and $E+\delta E$ and contribute to an increase in $\Omega$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The number of energy eigenstates that move from below $E+\delta E$ to above $E+\delta E$ is given by $N_{Y}\left(E+\delta E\right)$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] is thus the net contribution to the increase in $\Omega$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] If *Y dx* is larger than $\delta E$ there will be the energy eigenstates that move from below *E* to above $E+\delta E$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] They are counted in both $N_{Y}\left(E\right)$ and $N_{Y}\left(E+\delta E\right)$ , therefore the above expression is also valid in that case.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The first term is intensive, i.e. it does not scale with system size.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] In contrast, the last term scales as the inverse system size and will thus vanish in the thermodynamic limit.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Here *Z* is a factor that normalizes the sum of all the probabilities to 1, this function is known as the partition function.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] We now consider an infinitesimal reversible change in the temperature and in the external parameters on which the energy levels depend.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] As elaborated above, it is thought that the second law of thermodynamics is a result of the very low-entropy initial conditions at the Big Bang.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] From a statistical point of view, these were very special conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] On the other hand, they were quite simple, as the universe – or at least the part thereof from which the observable universe developed – seems to have been extremely uniform.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This may seem somewhat paradoxical, since in many physical systems uniform conditions (e.g. mixed rather than separated gases) have high entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The paradox is solved once realizing that gravitational systems have negative heat capacity, so that when gravity is important, uniform conditions (e.g. gas of uniform density) in fact have lower entropy compared to non-uniform ones (e.g. black holes in empty space).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] As for the reason why initial conditions were such, one suggestion is that cosmological inflation was enough to wipe off non-smoothness, while another is that the universe was created spontaneously where the mechanism of creation implies low-entropy initial conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] There are two principal ways of formulating thermodynamics, (a) through passages from one state of thermodynamic equilibrium to another, and (b) through cyclic processes, by which the system is left unchanged, while the total entropy of the surroundings is increased.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] These two ways help to understand the processes of life.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The thermodynamics of living organisms has been considered by many authors, including Erwin Schrödinger (in his book *What is Life?*) and Léon Brillouin.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] To a fair approximation, living organisms may be considered as examples of (b).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Approximately, an animal's physical state cycles by the day, leaving the animal nearly unchanged.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Animals take in food, water, and oxygen, and, as a result of metabolism, give out breakdown products and heat.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Plants take in radiative energy from the sun, which may be regarded as heat, and carbon dioxide and water.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Eventually they die, and their remains rot away, turning mostly back into carbon dioxide and water.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This can be regarded as a cyclic process.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Overall, the sunlight is from a high temperature source, the sun, and its energy is passed to a lower temperature sink, i.e. radiated into space.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This is an increase of entropy of the surroundings of the plant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Thus animals and plants obey the second law of thermodynamics, considered in terms of cyclic processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Living organisms may be considered as open systems, because matter passes into and out from them.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Thermodynamics of open systems is currently often considered in terms of passages from one state of thermodynamic equilibrium to another, or in terms of flows in the approximation of local thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The problem for living organisms may be further simplified by the approximation of assuming a steady state with unchanging flows.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] General principles of entropy production for such approximations are a subject of ongoing research.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Commonly, systems for which gravity is not important have a positive heat capacity, meaning that their temperature rises with their internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Therefore, when energy flows from a high-temperature object to a low-temperature object, the source temperature decreases while the sink temperature is increased; hence temperature differences tend to diminish over time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This is not always the case for systems in which the gravitational force is important: systems that are bound by their own gravity, such as stars, can have negative heat capacities.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] As they contract, both their total energy and their entropy decrease but their internal temperature may increase.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This can be significant for protostars and even gas giant planets such as Jupiter.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] When the entropy of the black-body radiation emitted by the bodies is included, however, the total entropy of the system can be shown to increase even as the entropy of the planet or star decreases.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The theory of classical or equilibrium thermodynamics is idealized.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] A main postulate or assumption, often not even explicitly stated, is the existence of systems in their own internal states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] In general, a region of space containing a physical system at a given time, that may be found in nature, is not in thermodynamic equilibrium, read in the most stringent terms.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] In looser terms, nothing in the entire universe is or has ever been truly in exact thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] For purposes of physical analysis, it is often enough convenient to make an assumption of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Such an assumption may rely on trial and error for its justification.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] If the assumption is justified, it can often be very valuable and useful because it makes available the theory of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Elements of the equilibrium assumption are that a system is observed to be unchanging over an indefinitely long time, and that there are so many particles in a system, that its particulate nature can be entirely ignored.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Under such an equilibrium assumption, in general, there are no macroscopically detectable fluctuations.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] There is an exception, the case of critical states, which exhibit to the naked eye the phenomenon of critical opalescence.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] For laboratory studies of critical states, exceptionally long observation times are needed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] In all cases, the assumption of thermodynamic equilibrium, once made, implies as a consequence that no putative candidate "fluctuation" alters the entropy of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] It can easily happen that a physical system exhibits internal macroscopic changes that are fast enough to invalidate the assumption of the constancy of the entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Or that a physical system has so few particles that the particulate nature is manifest in observable fluctuations.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Then the assumption of thermodynamic equilibrium is to be abandoned.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] There is no unqualified general definition of entropy for non-equilibrium states.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] There are intermediate cases, in which the assumption of local thermodynamic equilibrium is a very good approximation, but strictly speaking it is still an approximation, not theoretically ideal.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] For non-equilibrium situations in general, it may be useful to consider statistical mechanical definitions of other quantities that may be conveniently called 'entropy', but they should not be confused or conflated with thermodynamic entropy properly defined for the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] These other quantities indeed belong to statistical mechanics, not to thermodynamics, the primary realm of the second law.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The physics of macroscopically observable fluctuations is beyond the scope of this article.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The second law of thermodynamics is a physical law that is not symmetric to reversal of the time direction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This does not conflict with symmetries observed in the fundamental laws of physics (particularly CPT symmetry) since the second law applies statistically on time-asymmetric boundary conditions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The second law has been related to the difference between moving forwards and backwards in time, or to the principle that cause precedes effect (the causal arrow of time, or causality).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Irreversibility in thermodynamic processes is a consequence of the asymmetric character of thermodynamic operations, and not of any internally irreversible microscopic properties of the bodies.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Thermodynamic operations are macroscopic external interventions imposed on the participating bodies, not derived from their internal properties.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] There are reputed "paradoxes" that arise from failure to recognize this.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Loschmidt's paradox, also known as the reversibility paradox, is the objection that it should not be possible to deduce an irreversible process from the time-symmetric dynamics that describe the microscopic evolution of a macroscopic system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] In the opinion of Schrödinger, "It is now quite obvious in what manner you have to reformulate the law of entropy – or for that matter, all other irreversible statements – so that they be capable of being derived from reversible models.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The thermodynamic operation is externally imposed, not subject to the reversible microscopic dynamical laws that govern the constituents of the systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The statement of the law in this present article complies with Schrödinger's advice.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The cause–effect relation is logically prior to the second law, not derived from it.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This reaffirms Albert Einstein's postulates that cornerstone Special and General Relativity - that the flow of time is irreversible, however it is relative.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Cause must precede effect, but only within the constraints as defined explicitly within General Relativity (or Special Relativity, depending on the local spacetime conditions).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Good examples of this are the Ladder Paradox, time dilation and length contraction exhibited by objects approaching the velocity of light or within proximity of a super-dense region of mass/energy - e.g. black holes, neutron stars, magnetars and quasars.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The Poincaré recurrence theorem considers a theoretical microscopic description of an isolated physical system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] This may be considered as a model of a thermodynamic system after a thermodynamic operation has removed an internal wall.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The system will, after a sufficiently long time, return to a microscopically defined state very close to the initial one.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The Poincaré recurrence time is the length of time elapsed until the return.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] It is exceedingly long, likely longer than the life of the universe, and depends sensitively on the geometry of the wall that was removed by the thermodynamic operation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The recurrence theorem may be perceived as apparently contradicting the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] More obviously, however, it is simply a microscopic model of thermodynamic equilibrium in an isolated system formed by removal of a wall between two systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] For a typical thermodynamical system, the recurrence time is so large (many many times longer than the lifetime of the universe) that, for all practical purposes, one cannot observe the recurrence.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] One might wish, nevertheless, to imagine that one could wait for the Poincaré recurrence, and then re-insert the wall that was removed by the thermodynamic operation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] It is then evident that the appearance of irreversibility is due to the utter unpredictability of the Poincaré recurrence given only that the initial state was one of thermodynamic equilibrium, as is the case in macroscopic thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Even if one could wait for it, one has no practical possibility of picking the right instant at which to re-insert the wall.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The Poincaré recurrence theorem provides a solution to Loschmidt's paradox.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] If an isolated thermodynamic system could be monitored over increasingly many multiples of the average Poincaré recurrence time, the thermodynamic behavior of the system would become invariant under time reversal.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] James Clerk Maxwell imagined one container divided into two parts, *A* and *B*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Both parts are filled with the same gas at equal temperatures and placed next to each other, separated by a wall.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Observing the molecules on both sides, an imaginary demon guards a microscopic trapdoor in the wall.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] When a faster-than-average molecule from *A* flies towards the trapdoor, the demon opens it, and the molecule will fly from *A* to *B*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] The average speed of the molecules in *B* will have increased while in *A* they will have slowed down on average.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Since average molecular speed corresponds to temperature, the temperature decreases in *A* and increases in *B*, contrary to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] One response to this question was suggested in 1929 by Leó Szilárd and later by Léon Brillouin.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Szilárd pointed out that a real-life Maxwell's demon would need to have some means of measuring molecular speed, and that the act of acquiring information would require an expenditure of energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Likewise, Brillouin demonstrated that the decrease in entropy caused by the demon would be less than the entropy produced by choosing molecules based on their speed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] Maxwell's 'demon' repeatedly alters the permeability of the wall between *A* and *B*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/second-law-of-thermodynamics-p02] It is therefore performing thermodynamic operations on a microscopic scale, not just observing ordinary spontaneous or natural macroscopic thermodynamic processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] A **thermodynamic potential** (or more accurately, a **thermodynamic potential energy**) is a scalar quantity used to represent the thermodynamic state of a system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Similarly to the potential energy of the conservative gravitational field, defined as capacity to do work, various thermodynamic potentials have similar meanings.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The author of the term of thermodynamic potentials is Pierre Duhem in an 1886 work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Josiah Willard Gibbs in his papers used the term *fundamental functions*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Effects of changes in thermodynamic potentials can sometimes be measured directly, while their absolute magnitudes can only be assessed using computational chemistry or similar methods.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] One main thermodynamic potential that has a physical interpretation is the internal energy U.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] It is the energy of configuration of a given system of conservative forces (that is why it is called potential) and only has meaning with respect to a defined set of references (or data).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Expressions for all other thermodynamic energy potentials are derivable via Legendre transforms from an expression for U.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] In other words, each thermodynamic potential is equivalent to other thermodynamic potentials; each potential is a different expression of the others.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] In thermodynamics, external forces, such as gravity, are counted as contributing to total energy rather than to thermodynamic potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] For example, the working fluid in a steam engine sitting on top of Mount Everest has higher total energy due to gravity than it has at the bottom of the Mariana Trench, but the same thermodynamic potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] This is because the gravitational potential energy belongs to the total energy rather than to thermodynamic potentials such as internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] where T = temperature, S = entropy, p = pressure, V = volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Ni is the number of particles of type i in the system and μi is the chemical potential for an i-type particle.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The set of all Ni are also included as natural variables but may be ignored when no chemical reactions are occurring which cause them to change.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The Helmholtz free energy is in ISO/IEC standard called Helmholtz energy or Helmholtz function.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] It is often denoted by the symbol F, but the use of A is preferred by IUPAC, ISO and IEC.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] These five common potentials are all potential energies, but there are also entropy potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The thermodynamic square can be used as a tool to recall and derive some of the potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Note that the sum of internal energy is conserved, but the sum of Gibbs energy, or Helmholtz energy, are not conserved, despite being named "energy".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] They can be better interpreted as the potential to perform "useful work", and the potential can be wasted.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Thermodynamic potentials are very useful when calculating the equilibrium results of a chemical reaction, or when measuring the properties of materials in a chemical reaction.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The chemical reactions usually take place under some constraints such as constant pressure and temperature, or constant entropy and volume, and when this is true, there is a corresponding thermodynamic potential that comes into play.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Just as in mechanics, the system will tend towards a lower value of a potential and at equilibrium, under these constraints, the potential will take the unchanging minimum value.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The thermodynamic potentials can also be used to estimate the total amount of energy available from a thermodynamic system under the appropriate constraint.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] For each thermodynamic potential, there are thermodynamic variables that need to be held constant to specify the potential value at a thermodynamical equilibrium state, such as independent variables for a mathematical function.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] These variables are termed the **natural variables** of that potential.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] If a thermodynamic potential is not given as a function of its natural variables, it will not, in general, yield all of the thermodynamic properties of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] An exception for this rule is the *Ni* − *μi* conjugate pairs as there is no reason to ignore these in the thermodynamic potentials, and in fact we may additionally define the four potentials for each species.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] where the sums are over all species *j*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] If there is only one species, then we are done.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] But, if there are, say, two species, then there will be additional potentials such as $U[\mu _{1},\mu _{2}]=U-\mu _{1}N_{1}-\mu _{2}N_{2}$ and so on.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] If there are D dimensions to the thermodynamic space, then there are 2*D* unique thermodynamic potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] For the most simple case, a single phase ideal gas, there will be three dimensions, yielding eight thermodynamic potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The definitions of the thermodynamic potentials may be differentiated and, along with the first and second laws of thermodynamics, a set of differential equations known as the *fundamental equations* follow.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] where *δQ* is the infinitesimal heat flow into the system, and *δW* is the infinitesimal work done by the system, μi is the chemical potential of particle type i and Ni is the number of the type i particles.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] (Neither *δQ* nor *δW* are exact differentials, i.e., they are thermodynamic process path-dependent.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] By the second law of thermodynamics, we can express the internal energy change in terms of state functions and their differentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] and the equality holds for reversible processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Since U, S and V are thermodynamic functions of state (also called state functions), the above relation also holds for arbitrary non-reversible changes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Here the Xi are the generalized forces corresponding to the external variables xi.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The infinitesimals on the right-hand side of each of the above equations are of the natural variables of the potential on the left-hand side.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Similar equations can be developed for all of the other thermodynamic potentials of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] There will be one fundamental equation for each thermodynamic potential, resulting in a total of 2*D* fundamental equations.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] We can use the above equations to derive some differential definitions of some thermodynamic parameters.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] where xi and yi are conjugate pairs, and the yi are the natural variables of the potential Φ.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] where {*y**i* ≠ *j*} is the set of all natural variables of Φ except yj that are held as constants.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] This yields expressions for various thermodynamic parameters in terms of the derivatives of the potentials with respect to their natural variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] These equations are known as *equations of state* since they specify parameters of the thermodynamic state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] where, in the last equation, ϕ is any of the thermodynamic potentials (U, F, H, or G), and ${X,Y,\{N_{i\neq j}\}}$ are the set of natural variables for that potential, excluding Ni.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] In all, if the thermodynamic space is D dimensions, then there will be D equations for each potential, resulting in a total of *D* 2*D* equations of state because 2*D* thermodynamic potentials exist.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] If the D equations of state for a particular potential are known, then the fundamental equation for that potential (i.e., the exact differential of the thermodynamic potential) can be determined.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] This means that all thermodynamic information about the system will be known because the fundamental equations for any other potential can be found via the Legendre transforms and the corresponding equations of state for each potential as partial derivatives of the potential can also be found.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The above equations of state suggest methods to experimentally measure changes in the thermodynamic potentials using physically measurable parameters.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] which can be measured by monitoring the measurable variables of pressure, temperature and volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Changes in the enthalpy and internal energy can be measured by calorimetry (which measures the amount of heat *ΔQ* released or absorbed by a system).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Note that these measurements are made at constant {*Nj* } and are therefore not applicable to situations in which chemical reactions take place.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Again, define xi and yi to be conjugate pairs, and the yi to be the natural variables of some potential Φ.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] From these we get the Maxwell relations.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] There will be ⁠(*D* − 1)/2⁠ of them for each potential giving a total of ⁠*D*(*D* − 1)/2⁠ equations in all.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Again, define xi and yi to be conjugate pairs, and the yi to be the natural variables of the internal energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] This formula is known as an *Euler relation*, because Euler's theorem on homogeneous functions leads to it.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] (It was not discovered by Euler in an investigation of thermodynamics, which did not exist in his day.).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] As in the above sections, this process can be carried out on all of the other thermodynamic potentials.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Thus, there is another Euler relation, based on the expression of entropy as a function of internal energy and other extensive variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Yet other Euler relations hold for other fundamental equations for energy or entropy, as respective functions of other state variables including some intensive state variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Deriving the Gibbs–Duhem equation from basic thermodynamic state equations is straightforward.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The Gibbs–Duhem is a relationship among the intensive parameters of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] It follows that for a simple system with I components, there will be *I* + 1 independent parameters, or degrees of freedom.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] For example, a simple system with a single component will have two degrees of freedom, and may be specified by only two parameters, such as pressure and volume for example.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The law is named after Josiah Willard Gibbs and Pierre Duhem.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] As the internal energy is a convex function of entropy and volume, the stability condition requires that the second derivative of internal energy with entropy or volume to be positive.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] It is commonly expressed as $d^{2}U>0$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Since the maximum principle of entropy is equivalent to minimum principle of internal energy, the combined criteria for stability or thermodynamic equilibrium is expressed as $d^{2}U>0$ and $dU=0$ for parameters, entropy and volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] This is analogous to $d^{2}S<0$ and $dS=0$ condition for entropy at equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The same concept can be applied to the various thermodynamic potentials by identifying if they are convex or concave of respective their variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Where Helmholtz energy is a concave function of temperature and convex function of volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Where enthalpy is a concave function of pressure and convex function of entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Where Gibbs potential is a concave function of both pressure and temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] In general the thermodynamic potentials (the internal energy and its Legendre transforms), are convex functions of their extrinsic variables and concave functions of intrinsic variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The stability conditions impose that isothermal compressibility is positive and that for non-negative temperature, $C_{P}>C_{V}$ .
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Changes in these quantities are useful for assessing the degree to which a chemical reaction will proceed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The relevant potential depends on the reaction constraints, as shown in the following table.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] An infinitesimal change in the potential under the given constraints will be equal to $\sum _{i}\mu _{i}dN_{i}$ and this will be zero at equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] When the potential is not zero, this indicates a disequilibrium condition and the reaction will proceed in the direction which leads to zero potential.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Most commonly one considers reactions at constant p and T, so the Gibbs free energy is the most useful potential in studies of chemical reactions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] The Helmholtz free energy is useful when using a bomb calorimeter if the reaction is slow enough to be kept at a constant temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Enthalpy and internal energy are harder to control, since adiabatic conditions (constant entropy) are hard to establish.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] Nevertheless, enthalpy is useful in adiabatic isobaric combustion conditions such as gas turbines, jet engines, open flames, etc. while internal energy is useful in adiabatic isovolumetric combustion conditions such as adiabatic flames and certain internal combustion engines.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamic-potential] If the reaction in a bomb calorimeter is fast enough that negligible energy is lost during the reaction, it may be considered adiabatic, enabling the use of internal energy for calculations.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Historically, thermodynamics developed out of a desire to increase the efficiency of early steam engines, particularly through the work of French physicist Sadi Carnot (1824).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] His most important paper, "On the Moving Force of Heat", published in 1850, first stated the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In 1865 he named the concept of entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In 1870 he introduced the virial theorem, which applied to heat.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The initial application of thermodynamics to mechanical heat engines was quickly extended to the study of chemical compounds and chemical reactions.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Chemical thermodynamics studies the nature of the role of entropy in the process of chemical reactions and has provided the bulk of expansion and knowledge of the field.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Other formulations of thermodynamics emerged.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Statistical thermodynamics, or statistical mechanics, concerns itself with statistical predictions of the collective motion of particles from their microscopic behavior.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In 1909, Constantin Carathéodory presented a purely mathematical approach in an axiomatic formulation, a description often referred to as *geometrical thermodynamics*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A description of any thermodynamic system employs the four laws of thermodynamics that form an axiomatic basis.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The first law specifies that energy can be transferred between physical systems as heat, as work, and with the transfer of matter.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The second law defines the existence of a quantity called entropy, which describes the direction, thermodynamically, that a system can evolve and quantifies the state of order of a system and which can be used to quantify the useful work that can be extracted from the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In thermodynamics, interactions between large ensembles of objects are studied and categorized.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Central to this are the concepts of the thermodynamic *system* and its *surroundings*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A system is composed of particles, whose average motions define its properties, and those properties are in turn related to one another through equations of state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Properties can be combined to express internal energy and thermodynamic potentials, which are useful for determining conditions for equilibrium and spontaneous processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] With these tools, thermodynamics can be used to describe how systems respond to changes in their environment.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This can be applied to a wide variety of topics in science and engineering, such as engines, phase transitions, chemical reactions, transport phenomena, and even black holes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The results of thermodynamics are essential for other fields of physics and for chemistry, chemical engineering, corrosion engineering, aerospace engineering, mechanical engineering, cell biology, biomedical engineering, materials science, and economics, to name a few.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This article is focused mainly on classical thermodynamics which primarily studies systems in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Non-equilibrium thermodynamics is often treated as an extension of the classical treatment, but statistical mechanics has brought many advances to that field.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The history of thermodynamics as a scientific discipline generally begins with Otto von Guericke who, in 1650, built and designed the world's first vacuum pump and demonstrated a vacuum using his Magdeburg hemispheres.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Guericke was driven to make a vacuum in order to disprove Aristotle's long-held supposition that 'nature abhors a vacuum'.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Shortly after Guericke, the Anglo-Irish physicist and chemist Robert Boyle had learned of Guericke's designs and, in 1656, in coordination with English scientist Robert Hooke, built an air pump.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Using this pump, Boyle and Hooke noticed a correlation between pressure, temperature, and volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In time, Boyle's Law was formulated, which states that pressure and volume are inversely proportional.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Then, in 1679, based on these concepts, an associate of Boyle's named Denis Papin built a steam digester, which was a closed vessel with a tightly fitting lid that confined steam until a high pressure was generated.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Later designs implemented a steam release valve that kept the machine from exploding.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] By watching the valve rhythmically move up and down, Papin conceived of the idea of a piston and a cylinder engine.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] He did not, however, follow through with his design.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Nevertheless, in 1697, based on Papin's designs, engineer Thomas Savery built the first engine, followed by Thomas Newcomen in 1712.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Although these early engines were crude and inefficient, they attracted the attention of the leading scientists of the time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The fundamental concepts of heat capacity and latent heat, which were necessary for the development of thermodynamics, were developed by Professor Joseph Black at the University of Glasgow, where James Watt was employed as an instrument maker.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Black and Watt performed experiments together, but it was Watt who conceived the idea of the external condenser which resulted in a large increase in steam engine efficiency.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Drawing on all the previous work led Sadi Carnot, the "father of thermodynamics", to publish *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire* (1824), a discourse on heat, power, energy and engine efficiency.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The book outlined the basic energetic relations between the Carnot engine, the Carnot cycle, and motive power.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] It marked the start of thermodynamics as a modern science.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The first thermodynamic textbook was written in 1859 by William Rankine, originally trained as a physicist and a civil and mechanical engineering professor at the University of Glasgow.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The first and second laws of thermodynamics emerged simultaneously in the 1850s, primarily out of the works of William Rankine, Rudolf Clausius, and William Thomson (Lord Kelvin).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The foundations of statistical thermodynamics were set out by physicists such as James Clerk Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann, Max Planck, Rudolf Clausius and J.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Clausius, who first stated the basic ideas of the second law in his paper "On the Moving Force of Heat", published in 1850, and is called "one of the founding fathers of thermodynamics", introduced the concept of entropy in 1865.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Also Pierre Duhem in the 19th century wrote about chemical thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] During the early 20th century, chemists such as Gilbert N.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Guggenheim applied the mathematical methods of Gibbs to the analysis of chemical processes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] By a surface-level analysis, the word consists of two parts that can be traced back to Ancient Greek.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Firstly, *thermo-* ("of heat"; used in words such as *thermometer*) can be traced back to the root θέρμη *therme*, meaning "heat".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Secondly, the word *dynamics* ("science of force [or power]") can be traced back to the root δύναμις *dynamis*, meaning "power".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In 1849, the adjective *thermo-dynamic* is used by William Thomson.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In 1854, the noun *thermo-dynamics* is used by Thomson and William Rankine to represent the science of generalized heat engines.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Pierre Perrot claims that the term *thermodynamics* was coined by James Joule in 1858 to designate the science of relations between heat and power, however, Joule never used that term, but used instead the term *perfect thermo-dynamic engine* in reference to Thomson's 1849 phraseology.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The study of thermodynamic systems has developed into several related branches, each using a different fundamental model as a theoretical or experimental basis, or applying the principles to varying types of systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Classical thermodynamics is the description of the states of thermodynamic systems at near-equilibrium, that uses macroscopic, measurable properties.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] It is used to model exchanges of energy, work and heat based on the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The qualifier *classical* reflects the fact that it represents the first level of understanding of the subject as it developed in the 19th century and describes the changes of a system in terms of macroscopic empirical (large scale, and measurable) parameters.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A microscopic interpretation of these concepts was later provided by the development of *statistical mechanics*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Chemical thermodynamics is the study of the interrelation of energy with chemical reactions or with a physical change of state within the confines of the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The primary objective of chemical thermodynamics is to determine the spontaneity of a given transformation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Equilibrium thermodynamics is the study of transfers of matter and energy in systems or bodies that, by agencies in their surroundings, can be driven from one state of thermodynamic equilibrium to another.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The term 'thermodynamic equilibrium' indicates a state of balance, in which all macroscopic flows are zero; in the case of the simplest systems or bodies, their intensive properties are homogeneous, and their pressures are perpendicular to their boundaries.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In an equilibrium state there are no unbalanced potentials, or driving forces, between macroscopically distinct parts of the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Non-equilibrium thermodynamics is a branch of thermodynamics that deals with systems that are not in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Most systems found in nature are not in thermodynamic equilibrium because they are not in stationary states, and are continuously and discontinuously subject to flux of matter and energy to and from other systems.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The thermodynamic study of non-equilibrium systems requires more general concepts than are dealt with by equilibrium thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Many natural systems still today remain beyond the scope of currently known macroscopic thermodynamic methods.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Thermodynamics is principally based on a set of four laws which are universally valid when applied to systems that fall within the constraints implied by each.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In the various theoretical descriptions of thermodynamics these laws may be expressed in seemingly differing forms, but the most prominent formulations are the following.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This statement implies that thermal equilibrium is an equivalence relation on the set of thermodynamic systems under consideration.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Systems are said to be in equilibrium if the small, random exchanges between them (e.g.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Brownian motion) do not lead to a net change in energy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This law is tacitly assumed in every measurement of temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Thus, if one seeks to decide whether two bodies are at the same temperature, it is not necessary to bring them into contact and measure any changes of their observable properties in time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The law provides an empirical definition of temperature, and justification for the construction of practical thermometers.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The zeroth law was not initially recognized as a separate law of thermodynamics, as its basis in thermodynamical equilibrium was implied in the other laws.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The first, second, and third laws had been explicitly stated already, and found common acceptance in the physics community before the importance of the zeroth law for the definition of temperature was realized.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] As it was impractical to renumber the other laws, it was named the *zeroth law*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Adapted for thermodynamics, this law is an expression of the principle of conservation of energy, which states that energy can be transformed (changed from one form to another), but cannot be created or destroyed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Internal energy is a principal property of the thermodynamic state, while heat and work are modes of energy transfer by which a process may change this state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A change of internal energy of a system may be achieved by any combination of heat added or removed and work performed on or by the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] As a function of state, the internal energy does not depend on the manner, or on the path through intermediate steps, by which the system arrived at its state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The second law refers to a system of matter and radiation, initially with inhomogeneities in temperature, pressure, chemical potential, and other intensive properties, that are due to internal 'constraints', or impermeable rigid walls, within it, or to externally imposed forces.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] For systems that are initially far from thermodynamic equilibrium, though several have been proposed, there is known no general physical principle that determines the rates of approach to thermodynamic equilibrium, and thermodynamics does not deal with such rates.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The many versions of the second law all express the general irreversibility of the transitions involved in systems approaching thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In macroscopic thermodynamics, the second law is a basic observation applicable to any actual thermodynamic process; in statistical thermodynamics, the second law is postulated to be a consequence of molecular chaos.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This law of thermodynamics is a statistical law of nature regarding entropy and the impossibility of reaching absolute zero of temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This law provides an absolute reference point for the determination of entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The entropy determined relative to this point is the absolute entropy.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Alternative definitions include "the entropy of all systems and of all states of a system is smallest at absolute zero," or equivalently "it is impossible to reach the absolute zero of temperature by any finite number of processes".
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Absolute zero, at which all activity would stop if it were possible to achieve, is −273.15 °C (degrees Celsius), or −459.67 °F (degrees Fahrenheit), or 0 K (kelvin), or 0° R (degrees Rankine).
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] An important concept in thermodynamics is the thermodynamic system, which is a precisely defined region of the universe under study.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Everything in the universe except the system is called the *surroundings*.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A system is separated from the remainder of the universe by a *boundary* which may be a physical or notional, but serve to confine the system to a finite volume.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Segments of the *boundary* are often described as *walls*; they have respective defined 'permeabilities'.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Transfers of energy as work, or as heat, or of matter, between the system and the surroundings, take place through the walls, according to their respective permeabilities.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Matter or energy that pass across the boundary so as to effect a change in the internal energy of the system need to be accounted for in the energy balance equation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The volume contained by the walls can be the region surrounding a single atom resonating energy, such as Max Planck defined in 1900; it can be a body of steam or air in a steam engine, such as Sadi Carnot defined in 1824.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The system could also be just one nuclide (i.e. a system of quarks) as hypothesized in quantum thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] When a looser viewpoint is adopted, and the requirement of thermodynamic equilibrium is dropped, the system can be the body of a tropical cyclone, such as Kerry Emanuel theorized in 1986 in the field of atmospheric thermodynamics, or the event horizon of a black hole.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Boundaries are of four types: fixed, movable, real, and imaginary.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] For example, in an engine, a fixed boundary means the piston is locked at its position, within which a constant volume process might occur.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] If the piston is allowed to move that boundary is movable while the cylinder and cylinder head boundaries are fixed.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] For closed systems, boundaries are real while for open systems boundaries are often imaginary.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In the case of a jet engine, a fixed imaginary boundary might be assumed at the intake of the engine, fixed boundaries along the surface of the case and a second fixed imaginary boundary across the exhaust nozzle.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] As time passes in an isolated system, internal differences of pressures, densities, and temperatures tend to even out.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A system in which all equalizing processes have gone to completion is said to be in a state of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Once in thermodynamic equilibrium, a system's properties are, by definition, unchanging in time.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Systems in equilibrium are much simpler and easier to understand than are systems which are not in equilibrium.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] When a system is at equilibrium under a given set of conditions, it is said to be in a definite thermodynamic state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The state of the system can be described by a number of state quantities that do not depend on the process by which the system arrived at its state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] They are called intensive variables or extensive variables according to how they change when the size of the system changes.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The properties of the system can be described by an equation of state which specifies the relationship between these variables.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] State may be thought of as the instantaneous quantitative description of a system with a set number of variables held constant.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A thermodynamic process may be defined as the energetic evolution of a thermodynamic system proceeding from an initial state to a final state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] It can be described by process quantities.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] There are two types of thermodynamic instruments, the meter and the reservoir.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A thermodynamic meter is any device which measures any parameter of a thermodynamic system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In some cases, the thermodynamic parameter is actually defined in terms of an idealized measuring instrument.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] For example, the zeroth law states that if two bodies are in thermal equilibrium with a third body, they are also in thermal equilibrium with each other.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] This principle, as noted by James Maxwell in 1872, asserts that it is possible to measure temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] An idealized thermometer is a sample of an ideal gas at constant pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] From the ideal gas law *pV=nRT*, the volume of such a sample can be used as an indicator of temperature; in this manner it defines temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Although pressure is defined mechanically, a pressure-measuring device, called a barometer may also be constructed from a sample of an ideal gas held at a constant temperature.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A calorimeter is a device which is used to measure and define the internal energy of a system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] A thermodynamic reservoir is a system which is so large that its state parameters are not appreciably altered when it is brought into contact with the system of interest.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] When the reservoir is brought into contact with the system, the system is brought into equilibrium with the reservoir.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] For example, a pressure reservoir is a system at a particular pressure, which imposes that pressure upon the system to which it is mechanically connected.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The Earth's atmosphere is often used as a pressure reservoir.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The ocean can act as temperature reservoir when used to cool power plants.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The central concept of thermodynamics is that of energy, the ability to do work.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] By the First Law, the total energy of a system and its surroundings is conserved.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Energy may be transferred into a system by heating, compression, or addition of matter, and extracted from a system by cooling, expansion, or extraction of matter.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In mechanics, for example, energy transfer equals the product of the force applied to a body and the resulting displacement.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Conjugate variables are pairs of thermodynamic concepts, with the first being akin to a "force" applied to some thermodynamic system, the second being akin to the resulting "displacement", and the product of the two equaling the amount of energy transferred.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Thermodynamic potentials are different quantitative measures of the stored energy in a system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Potentials are used to measure the energy changes in systems as they evolve from an initial state to a final state.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The potential used depends on the constraints of the system, such as constant temperature or pressure.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] For example, the Helmholtz and Gibbs energies are the energies available in a system to do useful work when the temperature and volume or the pressure and temperature are fixed, respectively.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Thermodynamic potentials cannot be measured in laboratories, but can be computed using molecular thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] where T is the temperature, S the entropy, p the pressure, V the volume, $\mu$ the chemical potential, N the number of particles in the system, and i is the count of particles types in the system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Thermodynamic potentials can be derived from the energy balance equation applied to a thermodynamic system.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Other thermodynamic potentials can also be obtained through Legendre transformation.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Axiomatic thermodynamics is a mathematical discipline that aims to describe thermodynamics in terms of rigorous axioms, for example by finding a mathematically rigorous way to express the familiar laws of thermodynamics.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] The first attempt at an axiomatic theory of thermodynamics was Constantin Carathéodory's 1909 work *Investigations on the Foundations of Thermodynamics*, which made use of Pfaffian systems and the concept of adiabatic accessibility, a notion that was introduced by Carathéodory himself.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] In this formulation, thermodynamic concepts such as heat, entropy, and temperature are derived from quantities that are more directly measurable.
[src:thermodynamics-chemistry/thermodynamics] Theories that came after, differed in the sense that they made assumptions regarding thermodynamic processes with arbitrary initial and final states, as opposed to considering only neighboring states.
